# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/a-m-records-inc-v-napster-inc] While A&M Records served as the lead plaintiff, Napster was sued by 18 different record companies, all of which were members of the Recording Industry Association of America (RIAA).
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/a-m-records-inc-v-napster-inc] Napster was founded in 1999 by 18 year-old Shawn Fanning.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/a-m-records-inc-v-napster-inc] Napster provided a platform for users to download compressed digital music files, specifically MP3s, from other users' music libraries.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/a-m-records-inc-v-napster-inc] Unlike many peer-to-peer services, however, Napster included a central server that indexed connected users and files available on their machines, creating a searchable list of music available across Napster's network.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/a-m-records-inc-v-napster-inc] Napster's ease of use compared to other peer-to-peer services quickly made it a popular service for music enthusiasts to find and download digital song files for free.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/a-m-records-inc-v-napster-inc] The legacy record industry immediately took action against what it believed to be unauthorized copying of its copyrighted musical works within the Napster service.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/a-m-records-inc-v-napster-inc] The first suit was filed at the United States District Court for the Northern District of California.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/a-m-records-inc-v-napster-inc] The record companies alleged both contributory and vicarious copyright infringement by Napster, and filed a motion for a preliminary injunction in order to stop the exchange of the plaintiffs' songs on the service immediately.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/a-m-records-inc-v-napster-inc] Judge Marilyn Hall Patel of the United States District Court for the Northern District of California granted the preliminary injunction, on the grounds that the plaintiffs demonstrated a reasonable likelihood of success.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/a-m-records-inc-v-napster-inc] Napster appealed this ruling to United States Court of Appeals for the Ninth Circuit.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/a-m-records-inc-v-napster-inc] On appeal, the Ninth Circuit ordered a stay of the District Court's injunction, pending resolution.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/a-m-records-inc-v-napster-inc] This allowed Napster to continue its operations until the rendering of a judgment at the end of the hearings.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/a-m-records-inc-v-napster-inc] On the matter of direct copyright infringement, the Circuit Court agreed with the District Court's determination that Napster users were likely engaging in direct infringement of the plaintiffs' copyrights.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/a-m-records-inc-v-napster-inc] The Circuit Court dedicated much more of its opinion to Napster's attempted application of the fair use defense.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/a-m-records-inc-v-napster-inc] Creative works, such as the songs in question, are "closer to the core of intended copyright protection", thus favoring the plaintiffs.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/a-m-records-inc-v-napster-inc] In some cases, wholesale copying of a work may be allowable, with time shifting as an example.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/a-m-records-inc-v-napster-inc] Widespread wholesale transfer of plaintiffs' music negatively affected the market for CD sales and jeopardized the record industry's future in digital markets.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/a-m-records-inc-v-napster-inc] Thus, the Circuit Court rejected Napster's argument that file sharing by its users qualified for the fair use defense.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/a-m-records-inc-v-napster-inc] Napster's claims that it enabled legal sampling, space shifting, and permissive distribution (some artists had consented to the presence of their songs on the Napster service) were also rejected by the court.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/a-m-records-inc-v-napster-inc] Furthermore, the court found that Napster could control the infringing behavior of the service's users, and therefore had a duty to do so.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/a-m-records-inc-v-napster-inc] Therefore, Napster did not have a valid fair use defense.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/a-m-records-inc-v-napster-inc] The district court had ruled that the "law does not require knowledge of 'specific acts of infringement'," and rejected Napster's assertion that, because it could not distinguish between infringing and non-infringing files, it did not have knowledge of copyright infringement by its users.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/a-m-records-inc-v-napster-inc] The Ninth Circuit also held that Napster was not protected under *Sony Corp. of America v.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/a-m-records-inc-v-napster-inc] Universal City Studios, Inc.*, in which the Supreme Court ruled that media copying technologies were acceptable if they were unlikely to cause widespread copyright infringement beyond the original user.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/a-m-records-inc-v-napster-inc] The system was not designed to read the contents of MP3s or check for copyright ownership or permissions.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/a-m-records-inc-v-napster-inc] Because of Napster's failure to police within its means combined with the financial interest factor, the Ninth Circuit affirmed the District Court's finding of vicarious infringement.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/a-m-records-inc-v-napster-inc] The Ninth Circuit agreed with the District Court's finding that downloading MP3 files is not covered by the Audio Home Recording Act because online file sharing could spread unauthorized copies much more quickly than older forms of analog tape trading.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/a-m-records-inc-v-napster-inc] Napster also argued that the record companies waived their rights to copyright protection because they "hastened" the spread of MP3s on the Internet and had their own plans to get into the digital market.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/a-m-records-inc-v-napster-inc] The Ninth Circuit rejected Napster's claim that, by creating and providing digital files via the Internet, the plaintiffs had granted Napster an "implied license" to enable the copying of music files.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/a-m-records-inc-v-napster-inc] Finally, Napster argued that the plaintiffs were misusing copyright law to control online distribution, which Napster considered beyond the scope of the limited ownership rights provided by copyright.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/a-m-records-inc-v-napster-inc] The court rejected this argument as well, finding that MP3s were the same works as those that appeared on CDs, just in a different format, thus the plaintiffs had the ownership right to control the distribution of digital music.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/a-m-records-inc-v-napster-inc] Napster contended that the original District Court injunction shutting down its operations violated the company's First Amendment rights because it was overbroad and restricted other user activities beyond copyright infringement.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/a-m-records-inc-v-napster-inc] Recognizing that Napster's system simply indexed files with imperfect file names and did not automatically verify copyright ownership, the Circuit Court found that it was the plaintiffs' burden to notify Napster of any infringing files on the system, which Napster would then remove.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/a-m-records-inc-v-napster-inc] Napster was unable to comply and thus had to close down its service in July 2001.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/a-m-records-inc-v-napster-inc] The following year, Napster filed for bankruptcy and sold its assets to a third party.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/a-m-records-inc-v-napster-inc] The owners of the service settled with songwriters and music publishers, agreeing to pay $26 million.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/a-m-records-inc-v-napster-inc] Among a number of amicus briefs filed on behalf of both sides of the dispute, one particularly critical brief filed by a consortium of eighteen American copyright law professors argued that the district court misread the *Sony* precedent and took too narrow a view of fair use.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/a-m-records-inc-v-napster-inc] The professors argued that the overbroad nature of the injunction threatened the development and deployment of future peer-to-peer file-sharing networks on the Internet because it insisted on a restructuring that defeated peer-to-peer technology itself.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/a-m-records-inc-v-napster-inc] They also argued that the finding of contributory liability was erroneous because of Napster's significant non-infringing uses and because not all unauthorized uses within the system were copyright infringement.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/a-m-records-inc-v-napster-inc] A number of file-sharing networks surfaced in Napster's wake, including Morpheus, Grokster, and KaZaA, many of which faced their own legal challenges over infringing behavior by their users.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/a-m-records-inc-v-napster-inc] Grokster, Ltd.* was heard by the Supreme Court and is considered by many to be the sequel to the Napster case, addressing another technology that "outpaced the law." In the following years, BitTorrent, another P2P technology, became the target of copyright scrutiny.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/a-m-records-inc-v-napster-inc] Popular torrent trackers like the Pirate Bay faced long legal battles, but their opponents have had little success in shutting down these services permanently.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/act-of-congress] In the United States, an **act of Congress** is a statute passed by both the Senate and the House of Representatives of the United States Congress and signed into law by the president.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/act-of-congress] Acts may apply only to individual entities (called private laws), or to the general public (public laws).
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/act-of-congress] In the United States, acts of Congress are designated as either **public laws**, relating to the general public, or **private laws**, relating to specific institutions or individuals.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/act-of-congress] Since 1957, all acts of Congress have been designated as "Public Law X–Y" or "Private Law X–Y".
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/act-of-congress] X is the number of the Congress and Y refers to the sequential order of the bill (when it was enacted).
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/act-of-congress] 111–5 (American Recovery and Reinvestment Act of 2009) was the fifth enacted public law of the 111th United States Congress.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/act-of-congress] Public laws are also often abbreviated as Pub.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/act-of-congress] When the legislation of those two kinds are proposed, it is called public bill and private bill respectively.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/act-of-congress] The word "act", as used in the term "act of Congress", is a common, not a proper noun.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/act-of-congress] The capitalization of the word "act" (especially when used standing alone to refer to an act mentioned earlier by its full name) is deprecated by some dictionaries and usage authorities.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/act-of-congress] However, the Bluebook requires "Act" to be capitalized when referring to a specific legislative act.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/act-of-congress] The United States Code capitalizes "act".
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/act-of-congress] The term "act of Congress" is sometimes used in informal speech to indicate something for which getting permission is burdensome.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/act-of-congress] Reconsideration by the Congress after a presidential veto during its session.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/act-of-congress] A bill must receive a 2⁄3 majority vote in both houses to override a president's veto.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/act-of-congress] The president promulgates acts of Congress made by the first two methods.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/act-of-congress] If an act is made by the third method, the presiding officer of the house that last reconsidered the act promulgates it.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/act-of-congress] Under the United States Constitution, if the president does not return a bill or resolution to Congress with objections before the time limit expires, then the bill automatically becomes an act.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/act-of-congress] If the Congress is adjourned at the end of this period, then the bill dies and cannot be reconsidered (see pocket veto).
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/act-of-congress] If the president rejects a bill or resolution while the Congress is in session, a two-thirds vote of both houses of Congress is needed for reconsideration to be successful.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/act-of-congress] Promulgation in the sense of publishing and proclaiming the law is accomplished by the president, or the relevant presiding officer in the case of an overridden veto, delivering the act to the archivist of the United States.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/act-of-congress] The archivist provides for its publication as a slip law and in the United States Statutes at Large after receiving the act.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/act-of-congress] Thereafter, the changes are published in the United States Code.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/act-of-congress] Through the process of judicial review, an act of Congress that violates the Constitution may be declared unconstitutional by the courts.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/act-of-congress] A judicial declaration that an act of Congress is unconstitutional does not remove the act from the Statutes at Large or the United States Code; rather, it prevents the act from being enforced.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/act-of-congress] However, the act as published in annotated codes and legal databases is marked with annotations indicating that it is no longer good law.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/ahanchian-v-xenon-pictures-inc] The district court abused its judicial discretion in denying request for a one-week extension requested by Ahanchian's side to file his opposition and failed in denying Ahanchian's motion to allow a three-day late-filed opposition it construed as a Rule 60(b) motion.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/ahanchian-v-xenon-pictures-inc] The district judge also applied an incorrect standard in reviewing the late-filed request under FRCP 60(b), all the more so given that the late filing was only three days after the very short seven day deadline under United States District Court for the Central District of California local rules.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/ahanchian-v-xenon-pictures-inc] Accordingly, 9th Circuit Court of Appeals reversed the district court's grant of summary judgment, vacated the district court's award of attorneys' fees, and remanded the case for further proceedings.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/ahanchian-v-xenon-pictures-inc] The district court also stated that the denial was, in the alternative, based on a lack of Good cause.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/ahanchian-v-xenon-pictures-inc] This conclusion was also an abuse of discretion, per court's decision.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/ahanchian-v-xenon-pictures-inc] The Good Cause Law of Civility ensures that Cases are tried upon their merits.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/ahanchian-v-xenon-pictures-inc] There is a four-factor equitable test to determine excusable neglect.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/ahanchian-v-xenon-pictures-inc] Under Federal Rule of Civil Procedure - Title VI, when an "act may or must be done within a specified time, the court may, for good cause, extend the time on motion made after the time has expired if the party failed to act because of excusable neglect".
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-broadcasting-cos-inc-v-aereo-inc] Cable companies are required by the 1992 Cable Television Consumer Protection and Competition Act to negotiate for retransmission consent, usually paying broadcasters for the right to carry their signals.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-broadcasting-cos-inc-v-aereo-inc] Broadcasters argued that Aereo was a threat both to their business model by undermining the cable retransmission fees and the size of their audience.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-broadcasting-cos-inc-v-aereo-inc] Because the fees that cable companies paid for broadcast content could comprise up to 10% of a broadcaster's revenue, broadcasters objected to Aereo's re-distribution of this content without paying any fees.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-broadcasting-cos-inc-v-aereo-inc] Broadcasters have also identified Aereo as part of the cord-cutting trend among television audiences that poses a threat to broadcasters' advertising revenue.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-broadcasting-cos-inc-v-aereo-inc] District Court for the Central District of California granted an injunction against Aereo's rival FilmOn, a similar service.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-broadcasting-cos-inc-v-aereo-inc] However, the district court's injunction was legally binding only in its jurisdiction (including the West Coast of the continental United States, Alaska and Hawaii) and is currently being appealed to the Ninth Circuit Court of Appeals.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-broadcasting-cos-inc-v-aereo-inc] Other competitors were blocked from providing service in Los Angeles and Seattle by similar injunctions.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-broadcasting-cos-inc-v-aereo-inc] On March 1, 2012, two weeks before Aereo's initial launch in New York City, Aereo was sued for copyright infringement by a consortium of major broadcasters, including CBS Corporation's CBS, Comcast's NBC, Disney's ABC and 21st Century Fox's Fox.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-broadcasting-cos-inc-v-aereo-inc] The broadcasters argued that Aereo infringed their copyrighted material because Aereo's streams constituted public performances.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-broadcasting-cos-inc-v-aereo-inc] They sought a preliminary injunction against the company.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-broadcasting-cos-inc-v-aereo-inc] On July 11, Federal Judge Alison Nathan denied this injunction, citing as precedent the 2008 Cablevision case, which established the legality of cloud-based streaming and DVR services.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-broadcasting-cos-inc-v-aereo-inc] In response to the decision, the Aereo founder and CEO, Chet Kanojia, said, "Today's decision shows that when you are on the right side of the law, you can stand up, fight the Goliath and win." In a subsequent interview with CNET, Kanojia asserted, "With one step, we changed the entire TV industry.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-broadcasting-cos-inc-v-aereo-inc] The television industry and its evolution are now starting towards the Internet and that was stopped until Aereo came along....
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-broadcasting-cos-inc-v-aereo-inc] The plaintiffs appealed the decision to the U.S.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-broadcasting-cos-inc-v-aereo-inc] Court of Appeals for the Second Circuit.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-broadcasting-cos-inc-v-aereo-inc] Several other players in the industry, such as cable provider Cablevision, the Electronic Frontier Foundation, and the Consumer Electronics Association, filed amicus briefs.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-broadcasting-cos-inc-v-aereo-inc] On April 1, 2013, the federal appeals court upheld the lower court's ruling by finding that Aereo's streams to subscribers were not "public performances" and thus did not constitute copyright infringement.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-broadcasting-cos-inc-v-aereo-inc] The appeals court also affirmed the earlier district court decision that denied the broadcasters a preliminary injunction against Aereo.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-broadcasting-cos-inc-v-aereo-inc] In response, News Corporation Chief Operating Officer Chase Carey stated that the company is contemplating taking Fox off the air and converting it to a cable-only channel: "We need to be able to be fairly compensated for our content... we can't sit idly by and let an entity steal our signal.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-broadcasting-cos-inc-v-aereo-inc] We will move to a subscription model if that's our only recourse." Univision and CBS have also stated that they may also follow and convert to cable-only.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-broadcasting-cos-inc-v-aereo-inc] In October 2013, the broadcasters filed a petition to the United States Supreme Court to take up the issue.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-broadcasting-cos-inc-v-aereo-inc] On January 10, 2014, the Supreme Court agreed to hear the case.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-broadcasting-cos-inc-v-aereo-inc] The United States Department of Justice and United States Copyright Office also filed a joint brief in March 2014 that stated that Aereo's "system is clearly infringing." The Supreme Court heard oral arguments on April 22, 2014.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-broadcasting-cos-inc-v-aereo-inc] The Court decided in favor of the broadcasters on June 25 in a 6–3 decision and remanded the case.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-broadcasting-cos-inc-v-aereo-inc] The Court's decision describes Aereo as not being "simply an equipment provider" with an "overwhelming likeness to cable companies" that "performs petitioners' works 'publicly.'" Further, the Court adds that its decision should not discourage the emergence or use of different kinds of technologies.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-broadcasting-cos-inc-v-aereo-inc] Justices Scalia, Thomas and Alito dissented.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-broadcasting-cos-inc-v-aereo-inc] Writing for the dissenting minority, Scalia quoted from *Sony Corp. of America v.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-broadcasting-cos-inc-v-aereo-inc] Universal City Studios, Inc.* and noted that the broadcasters had made similar predictions regarding the VCR.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-broadcasting-cos-inc-v-aereo-inc] Like the final paragraph in that previous ruling, he stated that the Court should be in no position to make judgements on novel technologies and that Congress indeed has the task of determining if copyright laws should be modified to address those issues.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-broadcasting-cos-inc-v-aereo-inc] On November 21, 2014, the company filed for Chapter 11 bankruptcy in the United States Bankruptcy Court for the Southern District of New York.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-broadcasting-cos-inc-v-aereo-inc] It was later purchased by the DVR company TiVo for $1 million in March 2015.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-geophysical-union-v-texaco-inc-p01] One such system was in place during the 1980s, but Texaco declined to use it, citing its cumbersome bureaucratic requirements and its belief that the practice was fair use, leading several academic publishers, including the American Geophysical Union (AGU), to sue for copyright infringement.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-geophysical-union-v-texaco-inc-p01] At trial Leval found that Texaco's fair use defense failed on three of the four factors used to determine fair use.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-geophysical-union-v-texaco-inc-p01] The copies were used for the same informational purpose as the original articles, and Leval did not find that the ability they gave the scientists to bring them into the lab or home was sufficiently transformative.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-geophysical-union-v-texaco-inc-p01] The articles were copied in their entirety and adversely affected commercial opportunities for the publishers in the form of the lost revenue they otherwise would have made from licensing the photocopying and/or the sale of additional subscriptions to their journals.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-geophysical-union-v-texaco-inc-p01] Only on the second factor, the purpose of the work, did Leval hold for Texaco, since both the originals and the copies were used commercially.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-geophysical-union-v-texaco-inc-p01] Two years later, the Second Circuit took into account the Supreme Court's *Campbell v.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-geophysical-union-v-texaco-inc-p01] Acuff-Rose Music, Inc.* decision in the interim, which had recognized transformative use when it held parody to be protected under fair use.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-geophysical-union-v-texaco-inc-p01] Newman's majority opinion, amended twice over the year following, criticized Leval for having emphasized Texaco's commercial purpose, and held that the second-factor test, the purpose of the work, favored neither side, but otherwise affirmed his holding.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-geophysical-union-v-texaco-inc-p01] After further appeals were denied, Texaco settled the case.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-geophysical-union-v-texaco-inc-p01] Since the early 20th century, libraries had offered patrons the ability to make copies of documents, at considerable expense, with photostat machines.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-geophysical-union-v-texaco-inc-p01] In the 1960s, commercial xerographic photocopying machines became widely available in libraries, allowing patrons to duplicate reading material for personal use.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-geophysical-union-v-texaco-inc-p01] In 1973 several academic publishers filed suit against the federal government in the U.S.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-geophysical-union-v-texaco-inc-p01] Court of Claims, arguing that such photocopying by the library of the National Institutes of Health (NIH) and the National Library of Medicine (NLM) for the researchers in their employ was copyright infringement.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-geophysical-union-v-texaco-inc-p01] The government countered that the photocopying was fair use.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-geophysical-union-v-texaco-inc-p01] Davis held the government liable, but on appeal the court's full membership reversed.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-geophysical-union-v-texaco-inc-p01] Judge Oscar Hirsh Davis, writing for the majority, found the vague language in the Copyright Act of 1909 around copying work complicated the case.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-geophysical-union-v-texaco-inc-p01] Chief Judge Arnold Wilson Cowen, joined by Robert Lowe Kunzig and Philip Nichols Jr., dissented, arguing the majority had placed too much emphasis on facts favoring the defense.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-geophysical-union-v-texaco-inc-p01] It had not noted, as the trial judge had, that the 1909 Act was not at all vague about what copying meant, that the libraries routinely granted exceptions to the limits the majority had noted, and that measured in terms of the plaintiff's journals it *had* been adversely affected.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-geophysical-union-v-texaco-inc-p01] He included a portion of the trial judge's opinion, which he thought needed no elaboration, in his dissent.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-geophysical-union-v-texaco-inc-p01] Supreme Court, which granted *certiorari* and heard the case.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-geophysical-union-v-texaco-inc-p01] Justice Harry Blackmun recused himself, and after hearing oral argument the remaining justices were equally divided.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-geophysical-union-v-texaco-inc-p01] A short *per curiam* opinion was thus issued in 1975, allowing the Court of Claims's decision to stand.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-geophysical-union-v-texaco-inc-p01] Congress soon afterward passed the Copyright Act of 1976, the first major overhaul of copyright law since 1909.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-geophysical-union-v-texaco-inc-p01] Under those rules, meant to account for rapid improvements in information dissemination and storage technology, the Supreme Court found in 1984's *Sony Corp. of America v.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-geophysical-union-v-texaco-inc-p01] Universal City Studios, Inc.* that television viewers recording shows on their VCRs to watch later were making fair use of the copyrighted programming.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-geophysical-union-v-texaco-inc-p01] The following year, it provided some guidance for courts to apply the four fair use factors when it did so for the first time in *Harper & Row v.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-geophysical-union-v-texaco-inc-p01] Nation Enterprises*, holding that the publication of leaked excerpts of a forthcoming book did not meet the test.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-geophysical-union-v-texaco-inc-p01] The Act of 1976 did not include any specific provisions aimed at the bulk-photocopying issue that had been at the heart of *Williams & Wilkins*.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-geophysical-union-v-texaco-inc-p01] So, in response to a recommendation from Congress when it had been considering and developing the legislation, academic journal publishers had formed the Copyright Clearance Center (CCC) in 1977 to administer a licensing and royalty system.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-geophysical-union-v-texaco-inc-p01] Its Transactional Reporting System, established the following year, required that all subscribing institutions provide a report listing all the copies they made, which some found cumbersome.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-geophysical-union-v-texaco-inc-p01] In 1983 the CCC introduced another option, the Annual Authorization Service (AAS), which allowed unlimited copying for the payment of a blanket fee.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-geophysical-union-v-texaco-inc-p01] That option proved popular with large companies, and by 1991 CCC had 500 subscribers between the two plans, earning it around $27 million a year.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-geophysical-union-v-texaco-inc-p01] In 1990 federal judge Pierre Leval of the Southern District of New York, which hears many copyright cases due to the many media companies in New York City, published an influential *Harvard Law Review* article about fair use.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-geophysical-union-v-texaco-inc-p01] Texaco (since merged with Chevron) was a for-profit corporation that refined and sold oil products of all kinds.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-geophysical-union-v-texaco-inc-p01] It employed at the time of the suit between 400 and 500 scientists and engineers at six research centers in the U.S., one of which was located outside Beacon, New York, approximately 60 mi (97 km) north of Manhattan.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-geophysical-union-v-texaco-inc-p01] At the center, like its others, it maintained an internal library that, in addition to its holdings, subscribed to many scientific journals, for the benefit of its researchers.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-geophysical-union-v-texaco-inc-p01] Like other corporate internal libraries, Texaco's routinely supplied the company's researchers with photocopies of articles from the journals it subscribed to, both those that it believed might be of interest to them and those they specifically requested.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-geophysical-union-v-texaco-inc-p01] Unlike other companies, including most other major oil companies, while Texaco *had* purchased a license under CCC's per-transaction plan, CCC and its member publishers noticed that the company was photocopying much less than comparable licensees.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-geophysical-union-v-texaco-inc-p01] They concluded that Texaco was probably underreporting the total amount of copies it made.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-geophysical-union-v-texaco-inc-p01] According to copyright lawyer William Patry, who represented the publishers in the early portions of the suit, the goal of the suit was to disincentivize companies from trying to save costs that way and encourage them to pay more for the blanket plan allowing them to copy as much as they wanted.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-geophysical-union-v-texaco-inc-p01] In 1985, six journal publishers that licensed photocopying through CCC, led by the American Geophysical Union, sued Texaco in the Southern District of New York, alleging copyright infringement.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-geophysical-union-v-texaco-inc-p01] Texaco responded that per *Williams & Wilkins* the activity was protected under fair use.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-geophysical-union-v-texaco-inc-p01] Although the plaintiffs at the time of filing did not offer any evidence of infringement, he allowed the case to proceed on the grounds it was likely that it had, an unusual decision.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-geophysical-union-v-texaco-inc-p01] The evidentiary record reached 31 bound volumes.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-geophysical-union-v-texaco-inc-p01] In 1992 Leval rejected Texaco's claim of fair use and held that it was infringing the journal's copyrights.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-geophysical-union-v-texaco-inc-p01] The parties stipulated that the fair-use question would be contested on eight pieces—four articles, two notes, and two letters to the editor—from the *Journal of Catalysis*, published at the time by Academic Press (now part of Elsevier).
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-geophysical-union-v-texaco-inc-p01] The research center library received three subscriptions to it, at a cost of almost $2,500 ($6,000 in current dollars) annually.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-geophysical-union-v-texaco-inc-p01] They were kept in the file of one Texaco researcher, Donald Chickering, a PhD in chemical engineering who studied catalysis, the process by which small amounts of an additional chemical can speed up a reaction.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-geophysical-union-v-texaco-inc-p01] His job consisted of designing and conducting experiments in the labs.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-geophysical-union-v-texaco-inc-p01] On the first factor, the purpose of the secondary work, Leval observed that while it was typically a question of commercial or non-commercial use courts had increasingly been allowing commercial reuse to be offset by a sufficiently transformative use.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-geophysical-union-v-texaco-inc-p01] Texaco argued that the photocopies were transformative in that they contributed to its scientists' research.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-geophysical-union-v-texaco-inc-p01] Leval rejected that, since if it were true no copyright on scientific or scholarly research papers would survive.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-geophysical-union-v-texaco-inc-p01] Some precedent supported another of Texaco's first-factor arguments, that the copies were a necessary way of transmitting accurate information, in this case the "formulas, graphs and tables that set forth the results of studies and experiments".
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-geophysical-union-v-texaco-inc-p01] But Leval noted that the company's scientists had copied not just those pages but the entire articles, often before even reading them.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-geophysical-union-v-texaco-inc-p01] Lastly, Texaco had likened its photocopying to that upheld as fair use in *Williams & Wilkins*, arguing that its scientists, too, were using the previously published research as building blocks for their own progress in advancing science.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-geophysical-union-v-texaco-inc-p01] The company encouraged its scientists to publish their research in journals like those it photocopied from—pointing to 130 papers from them in the five years since the suit had been filed—and attend conferences; it also funded research at universities.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-geophysical-union-v-texaco-inc-p01] But Leval said that even though the Texaco scientists were not reselling their copied articles, "their research is being conducted for commercial gain.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-geophysical-union-v-texaco-inc-p01] Its purpose is to create new products and processes for Texaco that will improve its competitiveness and profitability." Thus the first factor of the fair-use test favored the publishers.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-geophysical-union-v-texaco-inc-p01] Turning to the second factor, the nature of the copyrighted work, Leval found the facts favored Texaco.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-geophysical-union-v-texaco-inc-p01] While, as he had observed in his *Harvard Law Review* article, copyright protection was especially important to the dissemination of scientific research due to the expense and risk involved.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-geophysical-union-v-texaco-inc-p01] But at the same time precedent was more generous to fair-use claims for works that primarily communicated factual information, since facts themselves cannot be copyrighted.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-geophysical-union-v-texaco-inc-p01] On the third factor, the portion of the work used, Leval held for the plaintiffs since the researchers had copied entire articles.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-geophysical-union-v-texaco-inc-p01] Texaco argued that these still did not amount to the entire work, since it was the publishers suing over their journals and not the individual authors.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-geophysical-union-v-texaco-inc-p01] By that standard, the company's researchers had copied only 4 percent of the publishers' journals in the time period at issue.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-geophysical-union-v-texaco-inc-p01] "This argument constitutes imaginative lawyering," Leval wrote, "but it does not prevail" as the authors had assigned copyright to the publishers in exchange for publication.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-geophysical-union-v-texaco-inc-p01] While the publisher registered only each issue with the Copyright Office, that was only for convenience's sake and did not logically make each issue a single, discrete copyrighted work.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-geophysical-union-v-texaco-inc-p01] As to the fourth factor, the impact on commercial opportunities for the copyrighted work, Texaco raised both factual and legal arguments against the publishers' contention that its photocopying had hurt their business.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-geophysical-union-v-texaco-inc-p01] If the photocopying were held infringing, Texaco argued that it would not be able to replace the copies with additional copies of the journals, since its researchers specifically needed the photocopies.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-geophysical-union-v-texaco-inc-p01] Leval found this "substantially correct" but that finding alone did not settle the question for Texaco.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-geophysical-union-v-texaco-inc-p01] Texaco pointed to the increase in the publishers' overall profits as evidence against market harm from its photocopying.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-geophysical-union-v-texaco-inc-p01] The copyright owner was only required to prove *potential* harm, in any event, Leval noted.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-geophysical-union-v-texaco-inc-p01] On the legal front, Texaco argued that courts should not overemphasize the fourth factor.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-geophysical-union-v-texaco-inc-p01] Since, the company said, there are some fair uses where the argument from the first three factors is strong enough, and the public need they address great, that to reject fair use on the ground of market harm would deny the public the benefit and go against the principles of fair use.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-geophysical-union-v-texaco-inc-p01] Leval agreed: "There is considerable force in Texaco's argument that this should not be the law ...
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-geophysical-union-v-texaco-inc-p01] Its arguments express a correct understanding of the law of fair use.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-geophysical-union-v-texaco-inc-p01] But the company could not make that argument in the instant case, Leval continued.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-geophysical-union-v-texaco-inc-p01] "This is not a case where hypothetical loss of revenue arguably converts fair use to infringement", he wrote.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-geophysical-union-v-texaco-inc-p01] "Here, without reaching the fourth factor, analysis of the other considerations strongly favors the plaintiffs' contention that Texaco's copying infringes the publishers' copyrights.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-geophysical-union-v-texaco-inc-p01] Courts may consider equitable factors besides the four related to the two works when assessing a fair-use defense, and Texaco made some arguments in that area.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-geophysical-union-v-texaco-inc-p01] First, it likened the case to both *Williams & Wilkins* and *Sony*, claiming they were similar enough as to not require separate evaluation.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-geophysical-union-v-texaco-inc-p01] Leval rejected that, observing that those two cases "do not purport to define the heartland of fair use.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-geophysical-union-v-texaco-inc-p01] "The argument has some force", Leval wrote, noting that Texaco was in a better position to make it for having used its own library than it would have been if its researchers made their own copies at public libraries.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-geophysical-union-v-texaco-inc-p01] But it still failed, as "Texaco uses three subscriptions to *Catalysis* to furnish copies to hundreds of scientists.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-geophysical-union-v-texaco-inc-p01] Nor, Leval wrote, did *Williams & Wilkins* help the company's case.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-geophysical-union-v-texaco-inc-p01] "Taking its own holding at face value, it strongly suggests that Texaco's use should be considered infringing", he said.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-geophysical-union-v-texaco-inc-p01] The Court of Claims had also cited the difficulty of managing the licensing of so many photocopies from different sources, something the CCC had been established to deal with in the interim, Leval noted.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-geophysical-union-v-texaco-inc-p01] Leval found Texaco's next argument, that the AAS plan that many CCC users had favored was irrelevant because some of the articles Chickering copied predated its establishment, "perversely struthian".
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-geophysical-union-v-texaco-inc-p01] The fact that members of the user community negotiated for something more advantageous by no means proves that the TRS was too burdensome to be practical", Leval wrote.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-geophysical-union-v-texaco-inc-p01] "Virtually every segment of this construct is flawed, illogical and contrary to the principle on which the copyright law is founded", Leval responded.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-geophysical-union-v-texaco-inc-p01] The authors' position on photocopying was irrelevant since they had surrendered copyright on their papers in order to get them published, and therefore they were likely to support any policy that extended the reach of their work, even at the expense of royalty payments.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-geophysical-union-v-texaco-inc-p01] "But the authors have not risked their capital to achieve dissemination.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-geophysical-union-v-texaco-inc-p01] And profit, Leval noted, was essential to copyright working for the public good.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-geophysical-union-v-texaco-inc-p01] So not only was Texaco's outrage legally irrelevant, it was "an odd argument, furthermore, to be made by an oil company that reported over $2.4 billion net income for fiscal 1989 on revenues of over $32 billion", Leval observed in a footnote.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-geophysical-union-v-texaco-inc-p01] The Second Circuit Court of Appeals took the case.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-geophysical-union-v-texaco-inc-p01] Stewart Jr., sitting by designation, was empaneled to hear it along with Ralph K.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-geophysical-union-v-texaco-inc-p01] Oral arguments were held in 1993; after which Stewart recused himself due to illness and was replaced by Jon O.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-geophysical-union-v-texaco-inc-p01] In late 1994, over a year later, a divided court affirmed Leval's ruling while criticizing some aspects of it.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-geophysical-union-v-texaco-inc-p01] Newman wrote the majority opinion, joined by Winter, while Jacobs dissented.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-geophysical-union-v-texaco-inc-p01] Since the district court decision, the Supreme Court had decided *Campbell v.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-geophysical-union-v-texaco-inc-p01] Acuff-Rose Music, Inc.*, a copyright case in which it recognized transformative use for the first time, holding that parody was protected under that concept.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-geophysical-union-v-texaco-inc-p01] Newman wrote that panel had incorporated that case's holdings, which had affected some of its interpretations even though it affirmed Leval's decision.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-geophysical-union-v-texaco-inc-p01] He found *Sony* to be the best applicable precedent.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-geophysical-union-v-texaco-inc-p01] After laying out the materials at issue (the articles in Chickering's file) and what the burden of proof was, Newman turned to the fair-use factors.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-geophysical-union-v-texaco-inc-p01] While Newman called Leval's analysis of the commercial-use question "insightful", he agreed the district judge had placed "undue emphasis" on Texaco's status as a for-profit company.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-geophysical-union-v-texaco-inc-p01] "Since many, if not most, secondary users seek at least some measure of commercial gain from their use, unduly emphasizing the commercial motivation of a copier will lead to an overly restrictive view of fair use", he observed.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-geophysical-union-v-texaco-inc-p01] He noted that *Campbell*, recently decided, had replaced the presumption against fairness for commercial reuse affirmed in *Sony* with the parallel transformative-use analysis.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-geophysical-union-v-texaco-inc-p01] Leval, Newman, said, had not recognized that the actual act of photocopying was not directly commercial.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-geophysical-union-v-texaco-inc-p01] But it was still relevant that Texaco was a commercial enterprise.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-geophysical-union-v-texaco-inc-p01] While he agreed that Texaco had raised a valid point, "it is overly simplistic to suggest that the 'purpose and character of the use' can be fully discerned without considering the nature and objectives of the user", Newman reiterated.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-geophysical-union-v-texaco-inc-p01] Precedents and legal commentary suggested that when there was both public and private benefit from secondary use, whether it was fair depended on how much accrued to the former interest.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-geophysical-union-v-texaco-inc-p01] "[W]e can confidently conclude that Texaco reaps at least some indirect economic advantage from its photocopying", said Newman.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-geophysical-union-v-texaco-inc-p01] Texaco reiterated its arguments that the photocopies allowed the articles to be used in the laboratory was sufficiently transformative.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-geophysical-union-v-texaco-inc-p01] But this "merely transforms *the material object* embodying the intangible article that is the copyrighted original work", Newman wrote.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-geophysical-union-v-texaco-inc-p01] He allowed that, again, Texaco's argument was not without value, as the direct copy was an improvement over the notes Chickering might have taken in the past.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-geophysical-union-v-texaco-inc-p01] "Nevertheless, whatever independent value derives from the more usable format of the photocopy does not mean that every instance of photocopying wins on the first factor.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-geophysical-union-v-texaco-inc-p01] Newman agreed with Leval that the "reasonable and customary use" claim that had been considered in *Williams & Wilkins* could no longer be made since the cooperative licensing agreements contemplated there were now a reality.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-geophysical-union-v-texaco-inc-p01] On the second factor, the nature of the copyrighted work, the publishers appealed Leval's finding for Texaco.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-geophysical-union-v-texaco-inc-p01] The publishers had contrasted his finding that the journal articles were purely factual communications by noting his statements about the importance of copyright law in protecting their work, and arguing that the articles were in fact creative works.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-geophysical-union-v-texaco-inc-p01] Newman reiterated Leval's conclusions as to the latter two, noting that *Williams & Wilkins* had also treated the articles at issue as separate works and *Sony* had set a high bar to cross for that holding.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-geophysical-union-v-texaco-inc-p01] Newman wrote at length in considering the fourth-factor analysis, the effect of the copying on the market for the original work.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-geophysical-union-v-texaco-inc-p01] He began by noting that *Campbell* had made this aspect of the analysis less important than before, when it had been "the single most important element of fair use", as the Supreme Court had characterized it in *Harper & Row*.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-geophysical-union-v-texaco-inc-p01] *Campbell* had changed that, instructing courts to weigh all four factors together.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-geophysical-union-v-texaco-inc-p01] This analysis was complicated by the fact that while there was a market for the journals, there was no discernible market for the individual articles that had been copied, making it hard to put a value on them.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-geophysical-union-v-texaco-inc-p01] Leval had approached the inquiry in terms of the effect on subscriptions, but Newman found this "of somewhat limited significance".
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-geophysical-union-v-texaco-inc-p01] The publishers might indeed have lost a few journal subscriptions, but as neither side had offered much in evidence either way, Newman did not see this area as offering much to help either side.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-geophysical-union-v-texaco-inc-p01] Newman found stronger ground when considering the question in terms of the loss of photocopying licensing revenue.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-geophysical-union-v-texaco-inc-p01] Leval had held this to favor the publishers, which Texaco said was error because it assumed that the publishers were entitled to that revenue, the question before the court.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-geophysical-union-v-texaco-inc-p01] Newman allowed that case law recognized some limitations on this issue, such as a market the original author cannot enter or has shown no interest in, but they did not apply here because the publishers, since *Williams & Wilkins*, had created the CCC and its licensing plans.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-geophysical-union-v-texaco-inc-p01] Texaco had argued that it did not follow that making it easier to pay affected the fair use evaluation, but Newman said that was logical.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-geophysical-union-v-texaco-inc-p01] Newman lastly found indirect evidence that Congress anticipated publishers being able to collect licensing fees for the photocopying of their work by libraries.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-geophysical-union-v-texaco-inc-p01] A section of the 1976 Copyright Act limited libraries' abilities to do that, for one thing.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-geophysical-union-v-texaco-inc-p01] The lost licensing revenue, Newman said, was the primary reason the court agreed with Leval that the publishers had prevailed on the fourth factor.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-geophysical-union-v-texaco-inc-p01] With two of the other factors also going their way, the majority affirmed Leval's conclusion that Texaco's copying was not fair use and thus infringement.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-geophysical-union-v-texaco-inc-p01] The Second Circuit issued its opinion in October 1994.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-geophysical-union-v-texaco-inc-p01] Two months later, it denied Texaco's petition for rehearing.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-geophysical-union-v-texaco-inc-p01] Most of the amendments made at that time were to its analysis of the fourth factor, the impact on commercial opportunities for the original work.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-geophysical-union-v-texaco-inc-p01] One of those changes was to specify more clearly the court's belief that in *Campbell* the Supreme Court had retreated from its earlier instruction (in *Harper & Row*) that the fourth factor was to be given the most importance.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-geophysical-union-v-texaco-inc-p01] In July 1995, it again amended the ruling.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-geophysical-union-v-texaco-inc-p01] Jacobs agreed with Newman and Winter's findings on the second and third factors.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-geophysical-union-v-texaco-inc-p01] He wrote at length on why he believed the majority had misread the first and fourth factors, which he believed favored Texaco.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-geophysical-union-v-texaco-inc-p01] Chickering's use is integral to transformative and productive ends of scientific research", Jacobs said.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-geophysical-union-v-texaco-inc-p01] "As to the fourth factor: the adverse effect of Dr.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-geophysical-union-v-texaco-inc-p01] Granting the majority its factual finding that Chickering had used the articles to inform his research, Jacobs pointed to the preamble of the statute governing fair use, which specifically mentioned "research" as a valid fair use of copyrighted material.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-geophysical-union-v-texaco-inc-p01] Jacobs also argued that the majority had given short shrift to the "reasonable and customary" aspect of the analysis; the copying of scholarly articles had been both since photocopiers had been invented.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-geophysical-union-v-texaco-inc-p01] It remained so despite the development of the CCC after *Williams & Wilkins*.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-geophysical-union-v-texaco-inc-p01] Chickering's notes were "important raw material in the synthesis of new ideas." Jacobs concluded.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-geophysical-union-v-texaco-inc-p01] Turning to the fourth factor, Jacobs agreed with the majority that the publishers had not established much of a loss from additional subscriptions Texaco might have purchased had it not been able to photocopy without paying license fees.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-geophysical-union-v-texaco-inc-p01] Leval had found, he noted, that Texaco would not necessarily purchase additional subscriptions if it could not photocopy, making it hard to quantify the loss to publishers from the copying.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-geophysical-union-v-texaco-inc-p01] Further, since the institutional subscription fee for *Catalysis* was double the individual rate, he suggested that publishers had assumed that the articles within would be copied and shared to some degree by readers at institutions and priced the subscription accordingly.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-geophysical-union-v-texaco-inc-p01] Jacobs parted company with the majority on the issue of lost photocopying license fees.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-geophysical-union-v-texaco-inc-p01] As a result of this fragmentation, it was necessary to determine the copyright status of every article copied prior to copying, and even then, an executive at Springer-Verlag had testified, it was "almost impossible to tell".
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-geophysical-union-v-texaco-inc-p01] The AAS's blanket license only eliminated some of the bureaucratic logging requirements, not the copyright confusion.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-geophysical-union-v-texaco-inc-p01] He called the majority's position that a previously fair use becomes less so once there is a licensing mechanism in place "sensible only to a point" since he believed it would not apply to parody or the use of quotations in a biography even if one existed.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-geophysical-union-v-texaco-inc-p01] Jacobs reviewed the equitable-factors analysis again with an eye towards the ultimate goal of copyright: public good.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-geophysical-union-v-texaco-inc-p01] For him it mattered that the authors of the journal articles had surrendered their copyrights, and with them any claim to royalties, to the publishers in order to assure maximum distribution and dissemination of their ideas.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-geophysical-union-v-texaco-inc-p01] The publishers had not argued that the revenue from the CCC had led directly to more journals being published, Jacobs wrote, citing statistics that showed the total amount of journals published doubled every 10–15 years.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-geophysical-union-v-texaco-inc-p01] "Clearly, the incentives currently in place for journal publishing assure a fair return." The court should have considered the incentives from the scientists' perspective, Jacobs argued, under which the process of exchanging ideas would now be more bureaucratically encumbered.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-geophysical-union-v-texaco-inc-p01] Texaco petitioned the Second Circuit for a rehearing *en banc* and the Supreme Court for *certiorari* to hear the case, but put both of them on hold pending settlement talks with the publishers.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-geophysical-union-v-texaco-inc-p01] In 1995 it announced that it would both pay a seven-figure settlement (the exact amount was confidential) to the CCC and retroactive license fees.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-geophysical-union-v-texaco-inc-p01] The CCC accomplished its goal of clearing up the legal uncertainties around the issue of institutional bulk photocopying through the lawsuit to encourage more companies to subscribe.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-geophysical-union-v-texaco-inc-p01] The 510 subscribers, most to the AAS, it had in 1990 grew to 3,500 AAS subscribers in 1993, after Leval's ruling.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-geophysical-union-v-texaco-inc-p01] By 2000 it had 10,000, a level that it remained at through 2007 (although without having grown its member author and publisher base to the same extent).
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-geophysical-union-v-texaco-inc-p02] Other courts have relied on *Texaco* to support the proposition that with *Campbell*, the Supreme Court, without saying so, retreated from its earlier insistence on the primacy of the fourth factor.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-geophysical-union-v-texaco-inc-p02] Michigan Document Services, Inc.*, a 1996 case also involving bulk photocopying, the Sixth Circuit allowed that the Supreme Court's denial of cert in *Texaco* might constitute an endorsement of this holding even as it announced it still considered the fourth factor first among equals.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-geophysical-union-v-texaco-inc-p02] In 2012 the Northern District of Georgia considered *Cambridge University Press v.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-geophysical-union-v-texaco-inc-p02] Becker*, a case involving academic photocopying by Georgia State University, which allowed digitized portions of works to be included in online coursepacks for students, the issue the Second Circuit had said it was not deciding in *Texaco*.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-geophysical-union-v-texaco-inc-p02] The plaintiff publishers had, in arguing the first factor favored them, likened the case to *Texaco* and *Michigan Document*, but Judge Orinda D.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-geophysical-union-v-texaco-inc-p02] Evans distinguished those cases as involving copying purely for commercial gain whereas in the instant case it was a nonprofit public university doing the copying.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-geophysical-union-v-texaco-inc-p02] Since the university also had a relationship with the CCC, she agreed that the lost licensing revenues decided the fourth factor in the publishers' favor.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-geophysical-union-v-texaco-inc-p02] Evans agreed that there was circular reasoning involved but found "no ideal solution" to the problem beyond evaluating all the factors independently, without regard to circularity.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-geophysical-union-v-texaco-inc-p02] In 2013 the American Institute of Physics invoked *Texaco* in bringing suit (again with other publishers as plaintiffs) against two law firms, one in Minneapolis and the other in Dallas, that they accused of similarly infringing unlicensed duplication of articles.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-geophysical-union-v-texaco-inc-p02] Both the District of Minnesota and the Northern District of Texas rejected the comparison.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-geophysical-union-v-texaco-inc-p02] The defendant firms practiced patent law, and printed the articles out not for archival research purposes, but to submit with clients' prosecutions as evidence of relevant prior art.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-geophysical-union-v-texaco-inc-p02] "The Court finds *Texaco* inapplicable here," wrote Judge Barbara M.G.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-geophysical-union-v-texaco-inc-p02] Scholarly critics of *Texaco* reiterated Jacobs' arguments, primarily on the circularity and intermediate copying issues, as well as adding some of their own.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-geophysical-union-v-texaco-inc-p02] Thomas found the Second Circuit's approach too focused on economic factors at the expense of the broader goal of copyright protection, leaving some questions unsatisfactorily answered or unaddressed.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-geophysical-union-v-texaco-inc-p02] The court should have, she wrote, followed the example of the Ninth Circuit in *Sega v.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-geophysical-union-v-texaco-inc-p02] Accolade*, where copied computer code served a transitory purpose in reverse engineering that bypassed the petitioner's licensing system to create games that could be played on its platform.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-geophysical-union-v-texaco-inc-p02] Like Jacobs, Cásarez felt that the "purpose and character of the use" should be evaluated in light of the possible ultimate benefit to the public, not the user.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-geophysical-union-v-texaco-inc-p02] Likewise, Cásarez argued that the court's analysis of the third and fourth factors had been driven by purely commercial considerations, as had the first factor.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-geophysical-union-v-texaco-inc-p02] Further, "[it] should have recognized that although Dr.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-geophysical-union-v-texaco-inc-p02] Chickering copied the complete articles as a preliminary step in his research, ultimately he would use very little of the original copyrighted works." The court was correct that the third factor favored the publishers, but should have assigned that less importance, Cásarez concluded.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-geophysical-union-v-texaco-inc-p02] Cásarez also wrote that the majority had gotten the distinction it drew between *Sony* and the instant case wrong.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-geophysical-union-v-texaco-inc-p02] The customers recording TV shows to watch them later, at more opportune times were likely to record them only once and then later tape over them, while researchers kept articles they had photocopied, even after drawing on them for research, until they needed to clear space in their files.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-geophysical-union-v-texaco-inc-p02] She also noted that the viewers taping programs had gotten them for free while Texaco had already paid for its subscriptions.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-geophysical-union-v-texaco-inc-p02] To Cásarez, the case called for Congress to supplement fair use with a personal-use exemption.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-geophysical-union-v-texaco-inc-p02] "If [it] is read to require an individual user to purchase a license or pay a royalty before he or she can duplicate a copyrighted article for personal use, then the copyright law is being applied not to enhance but rather to inhibit that user's ability to learn", she wrote.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-geophysical-union-v-texaco-inc-p02] A personal-use exemption would deal with that better than fair use, which Cásarez said has been judged and codified with commercial reuse in mind.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-geophysical-union-v-texaco-inc-p02] Looking back on *Texaco* in 2007, commentators at William & Mary focused on decisions that cited both it and *Campbell* to survey the state of courts' understanding of those precedents in ruling on fair use.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-geophysical-union-v-texaco-inc-p02] This ended in 2006 with *Bill Graham Archives v.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-geophysical-union-v-texaco-inc-p02] Dorling Kindersley, Ltd.* where the plaintiff had asserted market harm over unlicensed reproductions of posters and tickets to past Grateful Dead concerts used in the defendant's history of the band.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p01] American Samoa consists of the eastern part of the Samoan archipelago – the inhabited volcanic islands of Tutuila, Aunuʻu, Ofu, Olosega and Taʻū and the uninhabited Rose Atoll – as well as Swains Island, a remote coral atoll in the Tokelau volcanic island group.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p01] The total land area is 77 square miles (199 km2), slightly larger than Washington, D.C.; including its territorial waters, the total area is 117,500 square miles (304,000 km2), about the size of New Zealand.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p01] American Samoa has a tropical climate, with 90 percent of its land covered by rainforests.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p01] As of 2024, the population is approximately 47,400 and concentrated on Tutuila, which hosts the capital and largest settlement, Pago Pago.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p01] The vast majority of residents are indigenous ethnic Samoans, most of whom are fluent in the official languages, Samoan and English.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p01] Inhabited by Polynesians since prehistoric times, American Samoa was first contacted by Europeans in the 18th century.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p01] The islands attracted missionaries, explorers, and mariners, particularly to the highly protected natural harbor of Pago Pago.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p01] The United States took possession of American Samoa in the late 19th century, developing it into a major naval outpost; the territory's strategic value was reinforced by the Second World War and subsequent Cold War.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p01] In 1967, American Samoa became self-governing with the adoption of a constitution; its local government is republican in form, with separate executive, legislative, and judicial branches.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p01] It remains officially unorganized and is thus directly administered by the federal government.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p01] Due to the territory's strategic location, the U.S. military has a significant presence and plays a major role in its economy and society.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p01] The territory is noted for having the highest rate of military enlistment of any U.S. state or territory; as of 2021, the local U.S.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p01] Army recruiting station in Pago Pago ranked first in recruitment.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p01] Tuna products are the main exports, with the U.S. proper serving as the largest trading partner.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p01] Tourism is a nascent but underdeveloped sector, owing in part to the territory's relative geographic isolation, which also accounts for its high rate of poverty and emigration.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p01] Since the Deeds of Cession were signed in 1900 and 1904, Samoans have avoided further integration into the U.S. system.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p01] In 1949, the Department of the Interior moved to incorporate American Samoa through an Organic Act.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p01] Afraid that incorporation might undermine the Samoan culture and traditional land ownership, Samoan matai intervened and Congress halted incorporation.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p01] Instead, Samoa created its own government, the Samoan Fono, based on indigenous systems of governance.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p01] Since then, Samoans have declined to establish a federal district court and refused birthright citizenship; Samoa remains the only U.S. territory with its own immigration system.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p01] Many consider residents of American Samoa to be politically disenfranchised, with no voting representation in the U.S.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p01] Congress, though American Samoa itself has a democratic system of governance.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p01] However, many Samoans have prioritized indigenous culture and government over integration into the United States.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p01] American Samoa is the only permanently inhabited territory of the United States in which citizenship is not granted at birth, and people born there are considered "non-citizen nationals" with limited rights.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p01] A primary reason that Samoans do not have birthright citizenship is that it is opposed by many Samoans, as evidenced by the unanimous resolution of the Samoan Fono in 2021 against birthright citizenship, and multiple statements and actions by government officials over the decades.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p01] The elected representatives of American Samoan people unanimously fear that birthright citizenship would complicate the territory's political structure and lead to the erosion of indigenous governance, collective ownership of indigenous lands, and use of the Samoan language.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p01] The origin of the name "Samoa" means "holy center", taken from a compound of the Samoan *sa* ("sacred") and *moa* ("center").
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p01] The name is alternatively derived from a local chieftain named Samoa or an indigenous word meaning "place of the moa", a now-extinct bird, though the bird was known only from New Zealand.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p01] Although the sovereign state of Samoa changed its name from Western Samoa in 1997, the territory is also sometimes referred to as *Eastern Samoa* to distinguish it from its neighbor.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p01] Traditional oral literature of Samoa and Manuʻa talks of a widespread Polynesian network or confederacy (or "empire") that was prehistorically ruled by the successive Tui Manuʻa dynasties.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p01] Manuan genealogies and religious oral literature also suggest that the Tui Manuʻa had long been one of the most prestigious and powerful paramounts of Samoa.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p01] Oral history suggests that the Tui Manuʻa kings governed a confederacy of far-flung islands which included Tutuila, as well as smaller western Pacific chiefdoms and Polynesian outliers such as Uvea, Futuna, Tokelau, Tuvalu and bigger islands like the Samoa in the North.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p01] Contact with Europeans began in the early 18th century.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p01] Dutchman Jacob Roggeveen was the first known European to sight the Samoan Islands in 1722, calling them the "Baumann Islands" after one of his captains.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p01] The next explorer to visit the islands was Louis-Antoine de Bougainville, who named them the "Îles des Navigateurs" in 1768.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p01] British explorer James Cook recorded the island names in 1773, but never visited.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p01] The 1789 visit by Lapérouse was ended by an attack, on Tutuila island where Lapérouse's men were trying to obtain water.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p01] His second in command Capt. de Langle, and scientist Robert de Lamanon and several of his crew were surrounded by over a thousand Samoans and killed.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p01] La Pérouse named the island "Massacre Island", and the bay near Aasu is still called Massacre Bay.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p01] HMS *Pandora*, under the command of Admiral Edward Edwards (Royal Navy officer), visited the island in 1791 during its search for the H.M.S.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p01] Mission work in the Samoas had begun in late 1830 when John Williams of the London Missionary Society arrived from the Cook Islands and Tahiti.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p01] By the late nineteenth century, French, British, German, and American vessels routinely stopped at Samoa, as they valued Pago Pago Harbor as a refueling station for coal-fired shipping and whaling.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p01] The United States Exploring Expedition visited the islands in 1839.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p01] Meade of the USS *Narragansett* sailed from Hawai'i to Pago Pago to explore the establishment of a U.S. naval station.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p01] Peirce, the U.S. minister to Hawai'i, he was also tasked with negotiating a treaty that would secure American interests in Sāmoa.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p01] The *Narragansett* reached Pago Pago on February 14, and Meade informed High Chief Mauga of his intention to lease land for a naval base.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p01] Mauga granted the United States exclusive rights to build and maintain such a station in exchange for “the friendship and protection of the great government of the United States.” During his stay, Meade also arranged commercial port regulations for Pago Pago with Mauga.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p01] In March 1889, an Imperial German naval force entered a village in Samoa, and in doing so destroyed some American property.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p01] Three American warships then entered the Apia harbor and prepared to engage the three German warships found there.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p01] Before any shots were fired, a typhoon wrecked both the American and German ships.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p01] A compulsory armistice was then called because of the lack of any warships.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p01] Forerunners to the Tripartite Convention of 1899 were the Washington Conference of 1887, the Treaty of Berlin of 1889 and the Anglo-German Agreement on Samoa of 1899.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p01] The following year, the U.S. formally annexed its portion, a smaller group of eastern islands, one of which contains the noted harbor of Pago Pago.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p01] After the United States Navy took possession of eastern Samoa for the United States government, the existing coaling station at Pago Pago Bay was expanded into a full naval station, known as United States Naval Station Tutuila and commanded by a commandant.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p01] The Navy secured a Deed of Cession of Tutuila in 1900 and a Deed of Cession of Manuʻa in 1904 on behalf of the U.S. government.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p01] The last sovereign of Manuʻa, the Tui Manuʻa Elisala, signed a Deed of Cession of Manuʻa following a series of U.S. naval trials, known as the "Trial of the Ipu", in Pago Pago, Taʻu, and aboard a Pacific Squadron gunboat.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p01] Naval Station Tutuila, which was composed of Tutuila, Aunuʻu and Manuʻa, was officially renamed American Samoa.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p01] People of Manuʻa had been unhappy since they were left out of the name "Naval Station Tutuila".
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p01] In May 1911, Governor William Michael Crose authored a letter to the Secretary of the Navy conveying the sentiments of Manuʻa.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p01] The department responded that the people should choose a name for their new territory.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p01] The traditional leaders chose "American Samoa", and, on July 7, 1911, the solicitor general of the Navy authorized the governor to proclaim it as the name for the new territory.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p01] In 1918, during the final stages of World War I, the Great Influenza epidemic had taken its toll, spreading rapidly from country to country.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p01] The result of Poyer's quick actions earned him the Navy Cross from the U.S.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p01] With this distinction, American Samoans regarded Poyer as their hero for what he had done to prevent the deadly disease.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p01] The neighboring New Zealand territory at the time, Western Samoa, suffered the most of all Pacific islands, with 90% of the population infected; 30% of adult men, 22% of adult women and 10% of children died.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p01] Poyer offered assistance to help his New Zealand counterparts but was refused by the administrator of Western Samoa, Robert Logan, who became outraged after witnessing the number of quarantine ships surrounding American Samoa.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p01] Angered by this, Logan cut off communications with his American counterparts.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p01] After World War I, during the time of the Mau movement in Western Samoa (then a League of Nations mandate governed by New Zealand), there was a corresponding American Samoa Mau movement led by Samuelu Ripley, a World War I veteran who was from Leone village, Tutuila.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p01] After meetings on the United States mainland, he was prevented from disembarking from the ship that brought him home to American Samoa and was not allowed to return because the American Samoa Mau movement was suppressed by the U.S.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p01] Congress sent a committee to investigate the status of American Samoa, led by Americans who had a part in the overthrow of the Kingdom of Hawaii.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p01] Swains Island, which had been included in the list of guano islands appertaining to the United States and bonded under the Guano Islands Act, was annexed in 1925 by Pub.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p01] 68–75, following the dissolution of the Gilbert and Ellice Islands Protectorate by the United Kingdom.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p01] Marines stationed in Samoa outnumbered the local population and had a huge cultural influence.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p01] Young Samoan men from age 14 and above were combat-trained by U.S. military personnel.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p01] Samoans served in various capacities during World War II, including as combatants, medical personnel, code personnel, and ship repairmen.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p01] Department of Interior–sponsored attempt to incorporate American Samoa, was introduced in Congress.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p01] It was ultimately defeated, primarily through the efforts of Samoan chiefs, led by Tuiasosopo Mariota.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p01] The efforts of these chiefs led to the creation of a territorial legislature, the American Samoa Fono, which meets in the village of Fagatogo.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p01] In 1950 the Department of the Interior began to administer American Samoa.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p01] Navy-appointed governor was replaced by Peter Tali Coleman, who was locally elected.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p01] Although technically considered "unorganized" since the U.S.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p01] Congress has not passed an Organic Act for the territory, American Samoa is self-governing under a constitution that became effective on July 1, 1967.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p01] Territory of American Samoa is on the United Nations list of non-self-governing territories, a listing which is disputed by the territorial government officials, who do consider themselves to be self-governing.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p01] American Samoa and Pago Pago International Airport had historic significance with the Apollo Program.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p01] The astronaut crews of Apollo 10, 12, 13, 14, and 17 were retrieved a few hundred miles from Pago Pago and transported by helicopter to the airport prior to being flown to Honolulu on C-141 Starlifter military aircraft.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p01] While the two Samoas share language and ethnicity, their cultures have recently followed different paths, with American Samoans often emigrating to Hawaiʻi and the U.S. mainland and adopting many U.S. customs, such as the playing of American football and baseball.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p01] Samoans have tended to emigrate instead to New Zealand, whose influence has made the sports of rugby and cricket more popular in the western Samoan islands.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p01] Travel writer Paul Theroux noted that there were marked differences between the societies in Samoa and American Samoa.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p01] On August 13, 1999, the United Nations granted American Samoa "observer seat" status.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p01] Six days later, American Samoa officially recognized both Samoan and English as its official languages.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p01] In 2001 and 2003, the United States unsuccessfully sought to have American Samoa removed from the United Nations' decolonization list, arguing that the territory should not be considered a colony.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p01] American Samoans have a high rate of service in the U.S.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p01] Because of economic hardship, military service has been seen as an opportunity in American Samoa and other U.S.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p01] The federal Fair Minimum Wage Act of 2007 started gradual adjustments to the territorial minimum wage to bring it up to the level for U.S. states.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p01] On December 13, 1784, French navigator Jean-François de Galaup, comte de Lapérouse landed two exploration parties on Tutuila's north shore: one from the ship *Boussole* at Fagasā, and the other from *L'Astrolabe* at Aʻasu.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p01] One of the cooks, David, died of "scorbutic dropsy".
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p01] This incident gave Samoa a reputation for savagery that kept Europeans away until the arrival of the first Christian missionaries four decades later.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p01] On December 12, at Aʻasu Bay, Lapérouse ordered his gunners to fire one cannonball amid the attackers who had killed his men the day before and were now returning to launch another attack.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p01] On December 19, 1912, English writer William Somerset Maugham arrived in Pago Pago, allegedly accompanied by a missionary and Miss Sadie Thompson.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p01] His visit inspired his short story "Rain" which later became plays and three major motion pictures.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p01] The building still stands where Maugham stayed and has been renamed the Sadie Thompson Building.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p01] Today, it is a prominent restaurant and inn.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p01] On November 2, 1921, American Samoa's 13th naval governor, Commander Warren Jay Terhune, died by suicide with a pistol in the bathroom of the government mansion, overlooking the entrance to Pago Pago Harbor.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p01] His body was discovered by Government House's cook, SDI First Class Felisiano Debid Ahchica, USN.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p01] His ghost is rumored to walk about the grounds at night.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p01] On August 17, 1924, Margaret Mead arrived in American Samoa aboard the SS *Sonoma* to begin fieldwork for her doctoral dissertation in anthropology at Columbia University, where she was a student of Professor Franz Boas.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p01] Her work *Coming of Age in Samoa* was published in 1928, at the time becoming the most widely read book in the field of anthropology.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p01] The book has sparked years of ongoing and intense debate and controversy.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p01] Mead returned to American Samoa in 1971 for the dedication of the Jean P.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p01] In 1938, the noted aviator Ed Musick and his crew died on the Pan American World Airways S-42 *Samoan Clipper* over Pago Pago, while on a survey flight to Auckland, New Zealand.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p01] Sometime after takeoff, the aircraft experienced trouble, and Musick turned it back toward Pago Pago.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p01] While the crew dumped fuel in preparation for an emergency landing, an explosion occurred that tore the aircraft apart.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p01] On November 24, 1939, American Samoa's last execution to date was carried out.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p01] A man named Imoa of Fagatogo was convicted of stabbing a person named Sella to death and was hanged in the Customs House.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p01] The popular Samoan song "Faʻafofoga Samoa" is based on this, said to be the final words of Imoa.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p01] On January 13, 1942, at 2:26 a.m., a Japanese submarine surfaced off Tutuila between Southworth Point and Fagasa Bay and fired about 15 shells from its 5.5-inch deck gun at the U.S.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p01] Naval Station Tutuila over the next 10 minutes.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p01] The first shell struck the rear of Frank Shimasaki's store, ironically owned by one of Tutuila's few Japanese residents.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p01] Shimasaki had been interned as an enemy alien.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p01] The next shell caused slight damage to the naval dispensary, the third landed on the lawn behind the naval quarters known as "Centipede Row," and the fourth struck the stone seawall outside the customs house.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p01] The other rounds fell harmlessly into the harbor.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p01] As one writer described it, "The fire was not returned, notwithstanding the eagerness of the Samoan Marines to test their skill against the enemy ...
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p01] No American or Samoan Marines were wounded." Commander Edwin B.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p01] Robinson was bicycling behind Centipede Row and was wounded in the knee by a piece of shrapnel, and "a member of the colorful native Fita Fita Guard" received minor injuries; they were the only casualties.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p01] On August 24, 1943, First Lady Eleanor Roosevelt visited American Samoa and inspected the Fita Fita Guard and Band and the First Samoan Battalion of U.S.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p01] The fact that First Lady reviewed the troops led to further assurance that Tutuila Island was considered safe.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p01] Her presence underscored that World War II had passed by American Samoa.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p01] While the Fita Fita band played, Eleanor Roosevelt inspected the guard.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p01] On October 18, 1966, President Lyndon Baines Johnson and First Lady Lady Bird Johnson visited American Samoa.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p01] Johnson dedicated the "Manulele Tausala" ("Lady Bird") Elementary School in Nuʻuuli, which was named after her.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p01] Johnson is the only US president to have visited American Samoa, while Mrs.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p01] Johnson was the second First Lady, preceded by Eleanor Roosevelt in 1943.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p01] The territory's only hospital was renamed the LBJ Tropical Medical Center in honor of President Johnson.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p01] In the late 1960s and early 1970s, American Samoa played a pivotal role in five of the Apollo Program missions.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p01] The astronauts landed several hundred miles from Pago and were transported to the islands en route back to the mainland.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p01] President Richard Nixon gave three Moon rocks to the American Samoan government, which are currently on display in the Jean P.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p01] Haydon Museum along with a flag carried to the Moon on one of the missions.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p01] In November 1970, Pope Paul VI visited American Samoa in a brief but lavish greeting.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p01] On January 30, 1974, Pan Am Flight 806 from Auckland, New Zealand, crashed at Pago Pago International Airport at 10:41 pm, with 91 passengers aboard.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p01] 86 people were killed, including Captain Leroy A.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p01] Four of the five surviving passengers were seriously injured, with the other only slightly injured.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p01] The airliner was destroyed by the impact and succeeding fire.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p01] The crash was attributed to poor visibility, pilot error, or wind shear since a violent storm was raging at the time.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p01] In January 2014, filmmaker Paul Crompton visited the territory to interview local residents for a documentary film about the 1974 crash.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p01] As part of the Flag Day celebrations on April 17, 1980, a U.S.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p01] Navy P-3 Orion patrol plane from Patrol Squadron 50 took off with six skydivers from the U.S.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p01] Army's Hawaii-based Tropic Lightning Parachute Club.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p01] The airplane contacted the Solo Ridge-Mount Alava aerial tramway cable across Pago Pago harbor, which sheared off its vertical stabilizer.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p01] The aircraft crashed, demolishing a wing of the Rainmaker Hotel and killing all six crew members and one civilian.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p01] The six skydivers had already left the aircraft during a demonstration jump.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p01] On November 1, 1988, President Ronald Reagan signed a bill which created American Samoa National Park.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p01] On July 22, 2010, Detective Lieutenant Lusila Brown was fatally shot outside the temporary High Court building in Fagatogo.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p01] It was the first time in more than 15 years that a police officer was killed in the line of duty.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p01] The last was Sa Fuimaono, who drowned after saving a teenager from rough seas.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p01] On November 8, 2010, United States Secretary of State and former First Lady Hillary Clinton made a refueling stopover at the Pago Pago International Airport.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p01] She was greeted by government dignitaries and presented with gifts and a traditional kava ceremony.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p01] Mike Pence was the third sitting U.S. vice president to visit American Samoa (after Dan Quayle and Joe Biden) when he made a stopover in Pago Pago in April 2017.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p01] He addressed 200 soldiers here during his refueling stop.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p01] Secretary of State Rex Tillerson visited town on June 3, 2017.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p01] On September 28, 2009, at 17:48:11 UTC, an 8.1 magnitude earthquake struck 120 miles (190 km) off the coast of American Samoa, followed by smaller aftershocks.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p01] The quake occurred on the outer rise of the Kermadec-Tonga Subduction Zone.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p01] This is part of the Pacific Ring of Fire, where tectonic plates in the Earth's lithosphere meet, and earthquakes and volcanic activity are common.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p01] The quake struck 11.2 miles (18.0 km) below the ocean floor and generated an onsetting tsunami that killed more than 170 people in the Samoa Islands and Tonga.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p01] Four waves with heights from 15 feet (4.6 m) to 20 feet (6.1 m) high were reported to have reached up to one mile (1.6 km) inland on the island of Tutuila.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p01] The Defense Logistics Agency worked with the Federal Emergency Management Agency to provide 16 ft × 16 ft (4.9 m × 4.9 m) humanitarian tents to the devastated areas of American Samoa.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p01] American Samoa is classified in U.S. law as an unincorporated territory; the Ratification Act of 1929 vested all civil, judicial, and military powers in the President of the United States.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p01] In 1951, with Executive Order 10264, President Harry Truman delegated that authority to the Secretary of the Interior.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p01] On June 21, 1963 Paramount Chief Tuli Leʻiato of Fagaʻitua was sworn in and installed as the first Secretary of Samoan Affairs by Governor H.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p01] On June 2, 1967, Interior Secretary Stewart Udall promulgated the Revised Constitution of American Samoa, which took effect on July 1, 1967.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p01] The Governor of American Samoa is the head of government, and, along with the Lieutenant Governor of American Samoa, is elected on the same ticket by popular vote for a four-year term.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p01] The governor's office is located in Utulei.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p01] Since American Samoa is a U.S. territory, the President of the United States serves as the head of state but does not play a direct role in government.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p01] The Secretary of the Interior oversees the government, retaining the power to approve constitutional amendments, overrides the governor's vetoes, and nomination of justices.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p01] The legislative power is vested in the American Samoa Fono, which has two chambers.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p01] The House of Representatives has 21 members serving two-year terms, being 20 representatives popularly elected from various districts and one delegate from Swains Island elected in a public meeting.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p01] The Senate has 18 members, elected for four-year terms by and from the chiefs of the islands.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p01] The judiciary of American Samoa is composed of the High Court of American Samoa, a District Court, and village courts.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p01] The High Court and District Court are located in Fagatogo, near the Fono.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p01] The High Court is led by a Chief Justice and an Associate Justice, appointed by the Secretary of the Interior.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p01] Other judges are appointed by the governor upon the recommendation of the Chief Justice and confirmed by the Senate.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p01] American Samoa is an unincorporated and unorganized territory of the United States, administered by the Office of Insular Affairs, U.S.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p01] American Samoa's constitution was ratified in 1966 and came into effect in 1967.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p01] However, despite being de jure unorganized (as no Organic Act for it has been adopted by the U.S.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p01] Congress, instead leaving power vested in the U.S. president), American Samoa is de facto organized, with its politics taking place in the framework of a presidential representative democratic dependency (whereby an elected Governor is head of government) and of a pluriform multi-party system.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p01] Executive power is exercised by the governor.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p01] Legislative power is vested in the two chambers of the legislature.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p01] The American political parties (Republican and Democratic) exist in American Samoa, but few politicians are aligned with the parties.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p01] The judiciary is independent of the executive and the legislature.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p01] There is also the traditional village politics of the Samoa Islands, the "faʻamatai" and the "faʻa Sāmoa", which continues in American Samoa and independent Samoa, and which interacts across these current boundaries.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p01] The faʻa Sāmoa is the language and customs, and the faʻamatai are the protocols of the "fono" (council) and the chief system.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p01] The faʻamatai and the fono take place at all levels of the Samoan body politic, from the family to the village, to the region, to national matters.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p01] The ʻaiga is the family unit of Samoan society, which differs from the Western sense of a family in that it consists of an "extended family" based on the culture's communal socio-political organization.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p01] The matai (chiefs) are elected by consensus within the fono of the extended family and village(s) concerned.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p01] The matai and the fono, which are themselves made of matai, decide on the distribution of family exchanges and tenancy of communal lands.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p01] The majority of lands in American Samoa and independent Samoa are communal.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p01] A matai can represent a small family group or a great extended family that reaches across islands and to both American Samoa and independent Samoa.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p01] In 2010, voters rejected a package of amendments to the territorial constitution, which would have, among other things, allowed U.S. citizens to be legislators only if they had Samoan ancestry.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p01] In 2012, both the Governor and American Samoa's delegate to the U.S.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p01] Congress Eni Faleomavaega called for the populace to consider a move toward autonomy if not independence, with a mixed response.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p01] According to the Immigration and Nationality Act (INA), the people born in American Samoa – including those born on Swains Island – are "nationals but not citizens of the United States at birth".
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p01] If a child is born on any of these islands to any U.S. citizen, then that child is considered a national and a citizen of the United States at birth.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p01] All U.S. nationals have statutory rights to reside in all parts of the United States, and may apply for citizenship by naturalization after three months of residency by paying a fee, passing a test in English and civics, and taking an oath of allegiance to the United States.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p01] All U.S. nationals also have the right to work in the United States, except in certain government jobs that specifically require U.S. citizenship.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p01] The question of whether American Samoans should be granted citizenship is controversial in American Samoa, and the government of American Samoa is currently opposed to it.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p01] Those against citizenship worry that it would lead to federal judges overturning American Samoa's unique political system and land ownership customs, in which one must be at least 50% of Samoan ancestry to acquire land and land ownership is controlled by local families and *matai*.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p01] Those in favor of citizenship claim the law discriminates against them unfairly, restricting their voting rights and their ability to serve in many public sector professions.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p01] In 2012, a group of American Samoans sued the federal government seeking recognition of birthright citizenship for American Samoans in the case *Tuaua v.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p01] In an *amicus curiae* brief filed in federal court, American Samoan Congressman Faleomavaega supported the legal interpretation that the Citizenship Clause of the Fourteenth Amendment does not extend birthright citizenship to United States nationals born in unincorporated territories.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p01] Court of Appeals for the District of Columbia affirmed that Fourteenth Amendment citizenship guarantees did not apply to persons born in unincorporated territories and a year later the U.S.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p01] Supreme Court declined to review the lower court's decision.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p01] On July 20, 2021, the Legislature of American Samoa unanimously passed a resolution in support of the 10th Circuit Court's decision to reverse.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p01] As U.S. nationals, American Samoans can vote in local elections in the territory; however, if they live in other parts of the United States, they are not allowed to vote in federal, state or the vast majority of local elections unless they become U.S. citizens.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p01] The only federal office American Samoans elect directly is a non-voting delegate to the United States House of Representatives.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p01] Since the delegate's office was created in 1978, three people have held the seat: Democrat Fofō Iosefa Fiti Sunia (1981–1988); Democrat Eni Faleomavaega (1989–2015); and Republican Aumua Amata Radewagen (2015–).
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p01] American Samoans also participate in partisan presidential primaries, as well as send delegates to the Democratic and Republican National Conventions.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p01] Unique among U.S. territories, American Samoa has its own immigration law, separate from the laws that apply in other parts of the United States.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p01] U.S. nationals may freely reside in American Samoa.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p01] The American Samoan government, via its Immigration Office, controls the migration of foreign nationals to the islands.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p01] Special application forms exist for migration to American Samoa based on family or employment sponsorship.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p01] Unlike all other permanently inhabited U.S. jurisdictions (states, District of Columbia, Puerto Rico, U.S.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p01] Virgin Islands, Guam and Northern Mariana Islands), American Samoa is not considered a U.S. state for the purposes of the U.S.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p01] As a result, there is no path for immigrants to American Samoa to apply for U.S. citizenship, or U.S. nationality at all, without permanent residence in another U.S. jurisdiction.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p01] In addition, foreign nationals who do have lawful permanent residence in the United States may be considered to have abandoned it if they have moved to live in American Samoa, and time spent there does not count in the required period of U.S. presence for naturalization.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p01] U.S. nationals without U.S. citizenship (the status of most American Samoans) have the right to reside in all parts of the United States without immigration restrictions.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p01] They also have the same rights as lawful permanent residents to sponsor foreign family members to immigrate to the United States (they may sponsor spouses and unmarried children), but not the same rights as U.S. citizens (who may also sponsor parents, married children, and siblings).
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p01] Under American Samoan law, land ownership is subject to racial restrictions.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p01] Since 1900, there have been three main categories of land ownership: native, individual, and freehold.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p01] Native land, which makes up over 90% of all land in the territory, is land under the communal ownership of an ʻaiga, as opposed to the private ownership of an individual.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p01] Freehold land, which makes up only about 2% of the total, is land which was granted to foreigners before the U.S. took possession of the territory in 1900 and whose owners have not chosen to revert to native or individual land status.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p01] The American Samoa Code (Annotated) prohibits the transfer of ownership (whether by sale or otherwise) of any land other than freehold land to any person who has less than one-half native Samoan blood, which in this context includes both American and Western Samoa.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p01] In addition, it is prohibited to transfer ownership of any native (communal) land to any person who is not a full-blooded native Samoan: this includes any person who has any non-native blood whatsoever, even if they are more than one-half native Samoan.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p01] 10, 14 (1980), the Appellate Division of the High Court of American Samoa held that while these laws created a classification based on race, they did not violate the guarantees of equal protection and due process contained in the U.S.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p01] Constitution and the Revised American Samoan Constitution.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p01] Embassy in Samoa notes that: "In July 1997 the Constitution was amended to change the country's name from Western Samoa to Samoa.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p01] Samoa had been known simply as Samoa in the United Nations since joining the organization in 1976.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p01] The neighboring U.S. territory of American Samoa protested the move, feeling that the change diminished its own Samoan identity.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p01] American Samoa is administratively divided into three districts – Western, Eastern and Manuʻa – and two "unorganized" atolls, Swains Island and the uninhabited Rose Atoll.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p01] The districts are subdivided into counties and villages.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p01] Pago Pago, often cited as the capital of American Samoa, is one of the largest villages and is located on the central part of Tutuila island in Maʻoputasi County.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p01] American Samoa, located within the geographical region of Oceania, is one of only two possessions of the United States in the Southern Hemisphere, the other being Jarvis Island.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p01] Its total land area is 76.1 square miles (197.1 km2) – slightly larger than Washington, D.C. – consisting of five rugged, volcanic islands and two coral atolls.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p01] The five volcanic islands are Tutuila, Aunuʻu, Ofu, Olosega, and Taʻū.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p01] The coral atolls are Swains and Rose Atoll.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p01] Of the seven islands, Rose Atoll is the only uninhabited one; it is a Marine National Monument.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p01] American Samoa is the southernmost reach of the United States at fourteen degrees below the equator.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p01] Due to its positioning in the South Pacific Ocean, it is frequently hit by tropical cyclones between November and April.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p01] Rose Atoll is the easternmost point of the territory.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p01] American Samoa's Rose Atoll is the southernmost point of the United States.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p01] American Samoa is home to the National Park of American Samoa.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p01] Mount Pioa, nicknamed the Rainmaker, is 1,718 ft (524 m).
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p01] American Samoa is also home to some of the world's highest sea cliffs at 3,000 ft (910 m).
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p01] The Vailuluʻu seamount, an active submerged volcano, lies 28 miles (45 km) east of Taʻū in American Samoa.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p01] It was discovered in 1975 and has since been studied by an international team of scientists, contributing towards understanding of the Earth's fundamental processes.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p01] Growing inside the summit crater of Vailuluʻu is an active underwater volcanic cone, named after Samoa's goddess of war, Nafanua.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p01] In American Samoa forest cover is around 86% of the total land area, equivalent to 17,130 hectares (ha) of forest in 2020, down from 18,070 hectares (ha) in 1990.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p01] In 2020, naturally regenerating forest covered 17,130 hectares (ha) and planted forest covered 0 hectares (ha).
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p01] Of the naturally regenerating forest 1% was reported to be primary forest (consisting of native tree species with no clearly visible indications of human activity) and around 15% of the forest area was found within protected areas.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p01] For the year 2015, 0% of the forest area was reported to be under public ownership, 100% private ownership and 0% with ownership listed as other or unknown.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p01] American Samoa lies within two terrestrial ecoregions: Samoan tropical moist forests and Western Polynesian tropical moist forests.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p01] American Samoa has a tropical climate all year round with two distinct seasons, the wet and dry season.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p01] The wet season is usually between December and March and the dry season is from April through to September with the average daily temperature around 81–83 °F (27–28 °C) all year round.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p01] The climate is warm, tropical, and humid, averaging around 80 °F or 26.7 °C, with a variation of about 15 °F or 8 °C during the year.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p01] The southern hemisphere winter, from June to September, is the coolest time of the year.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p01] The summer months of December to March bring hotter temperatures, while the months from April to November are considered the "dry" season.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p01] Throughout the year, however, rain follows clouds blown in by the trade winds that rise from the east almost daily.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p01] The mountains of the Pago Pago area, standing over Pago Pago Harbor, catch these clouds, bringing an average of 200 inches or 5,100 millimeters of rainfall per year.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p01] Climate change in American Samoa encompasses the effects of climate change, attributed to man-made increases in atmospheric carbon dioxide, in the U.S. territory of American Samoa.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p01] The American Samoa Environmental Protection Agency (ASEPA) notes that the territory "has a fragile ecosystem" which is "directly and immediately impacted by global climate change".
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p01] The Human Rights Measurement Initiative finds that the climate crisis has worsened human rights conditions in American Samoa slightly (2.3 out of 6).
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p01] Human rights experts provided that the climate crisis has affected shores, fishers and resource availability, and that only a small group of people are able to connect the climate crisis with existing human rights conditions.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p02] The economic health of American Samoa reflects the trends in other populated U.S. territories, which are in turn dependent on federal appropriations.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p02] Federal dollars enter the economy through congressional appropriations, categorical grants, Social Security payments, and payments to Samoans retired from the military.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p02] Tuna canning is the backbone of the American Samoa economy.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p02] Cannery employment and local auxiliary businesses provide additional revenues for the territorial government.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p02] In the mid-1960s, efforts began to develop a tourism industry in American Samoa.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p02] Efforts were delayed due to issues with inconsistent airline service, insufficient high-quality accommodations, and the lack of well-trained workers in the hospitality and tourism industries.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p02] Agriculture and fishing still provide sustenance for local families.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p02] Employment on the island falls into three relatively equal-sized categories of approximately 5,000 workers each: the public sector, the single remaining tuna cannery, and the rest of the private sector.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p02] There are only a few federal employees in American Samoa and a few active duty military personnel, except members of the U.S.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p02] Coast Guard, military recruiters, and some Full-Time Support staff at the Pele Army Reserve unit that maintains the facility and provides cadre, training, and logistics support.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p02] The Pele US Army Reserve Center is in Tafuna, and a U.S.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p02] Army and United States Marine Corps recruiting station is in Nuʻuuli.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p02] The overwhelming majority of public sector employees work for the American Samoa territorial government.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p02] One tuna cannery is StarKist, which exports several hundred million dollars' worth of canned tuna to the United States each year.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p02] In early 2007, the Samoan economy was highlighted in the Congress at the request of Eni Faleomavaega, the Samoan delegate to the United States House of Representatives, as it was not mentioned in the minimum wage bill.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p02] It was given no exemption from the coming increases, which he protested as unfair to the Samoan economy.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p02] House Speaker Nancy Pelosi initially granted his request for an exemption, but backed down after being accused of serving special interests, since tuna packing company Chicken of the Sea was based in her district.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p02] Samoa Packing, a Chicken of the Sea subsidiary closed in 2009, citing both minimum wage increases and increasing foreign competition, with the latter as the "main reason".
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p02] Minimum wage in Samoa has been the topic of much debate, with the Samoan government and Chamber of Commerce strongly opposed, while businesses and workers hold nuanced views.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p02] From 2002 to 2007, real GDP of American Samoa increased at an average annual rate of 0.4 percent.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p02] The annual growth rates of real GDP ranged from −2.9 percent to +2.1 percent.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p02] The volatility in the growth rates of real GDP was primarily accounted for by changes in the exports of canned tuna.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p02] The tuna canning industry was the largest private employer in American Samoa during this period.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p02] In 2017, GDP in American Samoa decreased by 5.8%, but in 2018 it increased by 2.2%.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p02] From 2002 to 2007, the population of American Samoa increased at an average annual rate of 2.3 percent, and real GDP per capita decreased at an average annual rate of 1.9 percent.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p02] Agricultural production covers for domestic needs and only a small share of fruits and vegetables are exported.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p02] According to figures as of 2013, the ratio between import and export is almost balanced.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p02] Many residents rely on transfer payments from relatives living on the mainland or from federal subsidies.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p02] The unemployment rate was 29.8% in 2005 but improved to 23.8% as of 2010.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p02] In 2020, American Samoa's GDP was $709 million.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p02] The Fair Labor Standards Act of 1938 has contained special provisions for American Samoa since its inception, citing its limited economy.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p02] American Samoan wages are based on the recommendations of a Special Industry Committee meeting bi-annually.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p02] Originally, the act contained provisions for other territories, provisions which were phased out as those territories developed more diverse economies.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p02] In 2007, the Fair Minimum Wage Act of 2007 was passed, increasing the minimum wage in American Samoa by 50¢ per hour in 2007 and another 50¢ per hour each year thereafter until the minimum wage in American Samoa equals the federal minimum wage of $7.25 per hour in the United States.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p02] In response to the minimum wage increase, the Chicken of the Sea tuna canning plant was shut down in 2009, and 2,041 employees were laid off in the process.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p02] The other major tuna canning plant in American Samoa is StarKist, which began laying off workers in August 2010, with plans to lay off a total of 800 workers due to the minimum wage increases and other rising operation costs.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p02] American Samoa Governor Togiola Tulafono suggested that, rather than laying off minimum wage workers, the companies could reduce salaries and bonuses of top-tier employees.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p02] As in other U.S. territories, the U.S. federal government imposes payroll taxes and the equivalent self-employment tax on income from work in American Samoa, but not the federal income tax on income generated in American Samoa by its residents (except from work as U.S. government employees).
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p02] Instead, the government of American Samoa itself taxes the worldwide income of its residents, as well as the income generated there by nonresidents, largely under the same rules and rates as the U.S. tax code in effect in 2000, with certain modifications such as a minimum tax rate of 4%.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p02] A similar situation applies to corporations.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p02] In 1983, the use of citizenship in taxation by American Samoa (due to its incorporation of the U.S. tax code) was ruled unconstitutional.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p02] However, these taxes still apply to residents of a U.S. territory who acquired U.S. citizenship by birth or naturalization in a different part of the U.S. or by descent.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p02] It has been argued that this distinction based on place of birth, and not only residence or citizenship, is a rare case of unconstitutional tax discrimination, but it has never been challenged in court.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p02] The government of American Samoa itself does not impose estate or gift taxes.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p02] U.S. citizens (or anyone) cannot acquire this status after birth.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p02] American Samoa does not impose a sales tax, but it imposes a general import tax of 8%.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p02] American Samoa is an independent customs territory, whose importation rules and taxes differ from those applicable to other parts of the United States.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p02] Some aspects of telecommunications in American Samoa are, like other U.S. territories, inferior to that of the mainland United States; a recent estimate showed that American Samoa's Internet speed is slower than that of several Eastern European countries.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p02] In 2012 Michael Calabrese, Daniel Calarco, and Colin Richardson stated that American Samoa had the most expensive internet of any U.S. territory and that the speeds were only slightly superior to those of dial-up internet in the U.S.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p02] They also stated that many American Samoans are too poor to afford "high-speed internet".
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p02] American Samoa has 150 miles (240 km) of highways (estimated in 2008).
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p02] The maximum speed limit is 30 miles per hour.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p02] Ports and harbors include Aunuʻu, Auasi, Faleasao, Ofu and Pago Pago.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p02] The territory has three airports, all of which have paved runways.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p02] The main airport is Pago Pago International Airport, on the island of Tutuila.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p02] The Manuʻa group has two airports: Ofu Airport on the island of Ofu, and Fitiuta Airport on the island of Taʻū.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p02] According to a 1999 estimate, the territory has no merchant marine.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p02] On June 8, 1922, the first bus service on Tutuila began its operations.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p02] The *ʻaiga* bus system travels across the island of Tutuila.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p02] As of 2022, the population of American Samoa is estimated around 45,443 people.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p02] The 2020 census counted 49,710 people, 97.5% of whom lived on the largest island, Tutuila.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p02] About 57.6% of the population were born in American Samoa, 28.6% in independent Samoa, 6.1% in other parts of the United States, 4.5% in Asia, 2.9% in other parts of Oceania, and 0.2% elsewhere.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p02] At least 69% of the population had a parent born outside American Samoa.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p02] American Samoa is small enough to have just one ZIP code, 96799, and uses the U.S.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p02] Postal Service (state code "AS") for mail delivery.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p02] In the 2020 census, 89.4% of the population reported at least partial Samoan ethnicity, 83.2% only Samoan, 5.8% Asian, 5.5% other Pacific island ethnicities, 4.4% mixed, and 1.1% other ethnicities.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p02] The Samoan language was spoken at home by 87.9% of the population, while 6.1% spoke other Pacific island languages, 3.3% spoke English, 2.1% spoke an Asian language, and 0.5% spoke other languages; 47.2% of the population spoke English at home or "very well".
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p02] In 2022, Samoan and English were designated as official languages of the territory.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p02] At least some of the deaf population use Samoan Sign Language.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p02] Major Christian denominations on the island include the Congregational Christian Church in American Samoa, the Catholic Church, The Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints, and the Methodist Church of Samoa.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p02] Collectively, these churches account for the vast majority of the population.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p02] Gordon Melton in his book claims that Methodists, Congregationalists with the London Missionary Society, and Catholics led the first Christian missions to the islands.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p02] Other denominations arrived later, beginning in 1895 with the Seventh-day Adventists, various Pentecostals (including the Assemblies of God), Church of the Nazarene, Jehovah's Witnesses and The Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p02] CIA Factbook 2010 estimate shows the religious affiliations of American Samoa as 98.3% Christian, other 1%, unaffiliated 0.7%.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p02] World Christian Database 2010 estimate shows the religious affiliations of American Samoa as 98.3% Christian, 0.7% agnostic, 0.4% Chinese Universalist, 0.3% Buddhist and 0.3% followers of the Baháʼí Faith.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p02] According to Pew Research Center, 98.3% of the total population is Christian.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p02] Among Christians, 59.5% are Protestant, 19.7% are Catholic and 19.2% are other Christians.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p02] A major Protestant church on the island, gathering a substantial part of the local Protestant population, is the Congregational Christian Church in American Samoa, a Reformed denomination in the Congregationalist tradition.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p02] As of April 2023, The Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints website claims a membership of 16,512 (nearly 30% of American Samoa's entire population), with 43 congregations and five family history centers.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p02] Jehovah's Witnesses claim 210 "ministers of the word" and three congregations.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p02] The Catholic Church has at least 18 churches in the territory and 29 parishes under the Diocese of Samoa-Pago Pago (Diœcesis Samoa-Pagopagensis) which was created in 1982 by Pope John Paul II through the bull *Studiose quidem* and constitutes a suffragan see of the Archdiocese of Samoa-Apia.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p02] The bishop has his see in the Cathedral of the Holy Family in Tafuna and in the Co-cathedral of St.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p02] Of the ten secondary schools, five are operated by the American Samoa Department of Education; the other five are either administered by religious denominations or are privately owned.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p02] American Samoa Community College, founded in 1970, provides post-secondary education on the islands.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p02] American Samoa was home to one high school as of 1961, which existed due to the matai's pressure on the naval governor to transform the old Marine barracks at Utulei into a school.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p02] The teenagers of well-off and more politically connected families attended the school, which would later be known as Samoana High School.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p02] With a median age of 15, the demand for more high schools was increasing, and three new high schools were established by 1968.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p02] Another two soon followed, and by 1979, 2,800 high school students were attending six public and private high schools in American Samoa.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p02] Looking for a cost-effective way for educational reformation, Governor H.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p02] Rex Lee introduced the public television system in 1964.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p02] When TV was introduced, there were 6,000 educational programs produced annually; by 1981, only one series comprising 40-minute lessons in English-language skills was still aired.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p02] One of the side effects of advertising in popular programming from the U.S. was an increase in sales of over-the-counter drugs such as Pepto-Bismol and Sominex, with television being directly blamed for the decline of village life.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p02] The Samoan culture has developed over 3,500 years and largely withstood interaction with European cultures.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p02] It was adapted well to the teachings of Christianity.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p02] The Samoan language is still in use in daily exchange; however, English is widely used and also the legal official language.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p02] Besides Samoan language classes and cultural courses, all instructions in public schools are in English.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p02] The basic unit of the American Samoa culture is the *ʻaiga* (family).
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p02] It consists of both immediate and extended family.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p02] The *matai*, or chief, is the head of the ʻaiga.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p02] The chief is the custodian of all ʻaiga properties.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p02] A village (nuʻu) is made up of several or many ʻaiga with a common or shared interest.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p02] Each ʻaiga is represented by their chief in the village councils.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p02] The music of Samoa is a complex mix of cultures and traditions, with pre- and post-European contact histories.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p02] Since American colonization, popular traditions such as rap and hip hop have been integrated into Samoan music.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p02] Traditional Samoan musical instruments includes several different distinctive instruments, including a fala, which is a rolled-up mat beaten with sticks and several types of slit drum.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p02] The main sports played in American Samoa are football, Samoan cricket, canoeing, yachting, basketball, golf, netball, tennis, rugby, table tennis, boxing, bowling, volleyball, and fishing tournaments.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p02] Some current and former sports clubs are the American Samoa Tennis Association, Rugby Unions, Lavalava Golf Club, and Gamefish Association.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p02] Leagues improved and organized better after the completion of the Veterans Memorial Stadium.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p02] The 1997 South Pacific Mini Games were the biggest international event ever to take place in American Samoa.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p02] The bid to host the games for the 23 participating countries was approved in May 1993.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p02] Lutali appointed Fuga Teleso to head the task force charged with game preparations, including the construction of a stadium.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p02] The Governor later handed the task force on preparations to Lieutenant Governor Togiola.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p02] The task force merged with the American Samoa National Olympics Committee to better coordinate and facilitate preparations.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p02] Willis Construction built the 1,500-seat stands.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p02] The Department of Public Safety trained its force for special games security.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p02] The opening ceremony became extravagant where the U.S.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p02] Army Reserve carried the torch from Tula and Leone.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p02] About 2,000 athletes, coaches, and sponsors attended from 19 countries and competed in 11 sports at the game.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p02] American Samoa fielded a team of 248 athletes.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p02] The team won 48 medals, 22 of which were gold medals, and American Samoa came in fourth overall in the ratings.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p02] American Samoa Rotary Club honored Fuga Tolani Teleso with the community's top award, the Paul Harris Fellowship Award, for his work on constructing the Veterans Memorial Stadium.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p02] In 1982, yachters competed in the Hobie World Championship held in Tahiti.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p02] American Samoa beat the Apia team by half a point and won the Samoa Cup.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p02] In 1983, a team coached by Adele Satele-Galeai brought home the winning trophy from the Regional women's volleyball tournament in Hawaii.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p02] Also in 1983, the South Pacific Games were held in Apia.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p02] American Samoa received 13 medals: four gold, four silver, and five bronze.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p02] That same year, three junior golfers made the cut out of 1,000 players to attend the World Junior Golf Tournament in San Diego, California.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p02] In 1987, American Samoa became the 167th member of the International Olympic Committee.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p02] The first South Pacific Junior Tennis Tournament was held at the Tafuna courts in January 1990.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p02] Tony Solaita was the first American Samoan to play in Major League Baseball.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p02] There are thirty players from American Samoa in the National Football League (NFL) as of 2015 and over 200 play Div.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p02] Some American Samoan NFL football players are Shalom Luani, Junior Siavii, Jonathan Fanene, Mosi Tatupu, Shaun Nua, Isaac Sopoaga, and Daniel Teʻo-Nesheim.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p02] After World War II, a Welfare and Recreation Department was created.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p02] This department arranged bowling, softball, badminton tournaments, basketball, and volleyball at various Tutuila locations.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p02] Boxing matches and dancing also became popular activities.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p02] About 30 ethnic Samoans, all from American Samoa, currently play in the National Football League, and more than 200 play NCAA Division I college football.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p02] In recent years, it has been estimated that a Samoan male (either an American Samoan, or a Samoan living in the mainland United States) is anywhere from 40 to 56 times more likely to play in the NFL than a non-Samoan American, giving American Samoa the nickname "Football Islands".
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p02] Samoans are the most disproportionately overrepresented ethnic group in the National Football League.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p02] Six-time All-Pro Junior Seau was one of the most famous Americans of Samoan heritage ever to play in the NFL, having been elected to the NFL 1990s All-Decade Team and Pro Football Hall of Fame.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p02] The football culture was featured on *60 Minutes* on January 17, 2010.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p02] At the 2016 Republican National Convention, American Samoa's delegation said American Samoa is "the greatest exporter of NFL players".
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p02] The Football Federation American Samoa oversees men's and women's national teams.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p02] The men's national team made its international debut in the 1983 South Pacific Games, losing its opener against Western Samoa.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p02] Despite scoring a win against Wallis and Futuna, the team did not exit the group stage.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p02] The team lost to Australia 31–0 in a FIFA World Cup qualifying match on April 11, 2001, but on November 22, 2011, they finally won their first FIFA World Cup qualifier, beating Tonga 2–1.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p02] The appearance of American Samoa's Jaiyah Saelua, who is faʻafafine, in the contest "apparently became the first transgender player to compete on a World Cup stage".
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p02] The women's national team made its international debut at the 1998 OFC Women's Championship, losing both of its matches: 21–0 to Australia and 9–0 to Papua New Guinea.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p02] The American Samoan men's national team features in the highly rated 2014 British film *Next Goal Wins*.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p02] The film documents the team's 2014 FIFA World Cup qualifying campaign, in which they achieved their first-ever international win.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p02] Saelua and Nicky Salapu, the man famous for being the goalkeeper during the team's 31–0 loss to Australia in 2001, feature prominently in the film.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p02] A feature film adaptation of the documentary was released in 2023 and was directed by Taika Waititi.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p02] The American Samoa national rugby league team represents the country in international rugby league.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p02] The team competed in the 1988, 1992, 1998 and 2004 Pacific Cup competitions.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p02] The team has also competed in the 2003 and 2004 World Sevens qualifiers in the 2005 World Sevens.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p02] America Samoa's first match in the international Rugby League was in the 1988 Pacific Cup against Tonga, Tonga won the match 38–14 which is still the biggest loss by an American Samoan side.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p02] American Samoa's biggest win was in 2004 against New Caledonia with a final score of 62–6.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p02] American Samoa gets broadcasts of the National Rugby League in Australia on free-to-air television.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p02] There is also a new movement that aims to set up a four-team domestic competition in American Samoa.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p02] Rugby union is a growing sport in American Samoa.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p02] The first rugby game recorded in American Samoa was in 1924, since then the development of the game had been heavily overshadowed by the influence of American football during the 1970s.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p02] The highest governing body of rugby in American Samoa is the American Samoa Rugby Union which was founded in 1990 and was not affiliated with the IRB until 2012.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p02] Internationally, two American Samoans have played for the New Zealand national rugby union team, known as the All Blacks.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p02] Frank Solomon (born in Pago Pago) became the first American national of Samoan descent to play for a New Zealand team.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p02] Considered a pacific pioneer in New Zealand rugby, Solomon scored a try against Australia in the inaugural Bledisloe Cup match in 1932, which New Zealand won 21–13.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p02] The second American Samoan to play for the All Blacks is Jerome Kaino (born in Fagaʻalu).
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p02] A native of Leone, Kaino moved to New Zealand when he was four.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p02] In 2004, at age 21, he played his first match for New Zealand against the Barbarians where he scored his first try, contributing to New Zealand's 47–19 victory that resulted in him becoming a man of the match.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p02] He also played a crucial role in the Rugby World Cup 2011 playing every match in the tournament.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p02] He scored four tries in the event which led to New Zealand winning the final against France 8–7.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p02] Kaino was also a key member of the 2015 Rugby World Cup squad, where he played every match including a try he scored in the quarterfinals against France which New Zealand won 62–13.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p02] He scored again in the semifinals against South Africa, which New Zealand won 20–18.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p02] He played in the World Cup final against Australia where New Zealand won again 34–17 to become world champions for a record three times (1987, 2011, and 2015).
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p02] Kaino is one of twenty New Zealand rugby players to have won the Rugby World Cup twice, back to back in 2011 and 2015.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p02] In August 2015, the American Samoa Rugby Union Board selected Leota Toma Patu from the village of Leone as the coach for the Talavalu 15 men's team that represented American Samoa at the Ocean Cup 2015 in Papua New Guinea.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p02] A team from the Bureau of Outdoor Recreation conducted a parks survey on American Samoa in the 1960s.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p02] Their team recommended sites at Cape Taputapu, Leʻala at Vailoatai, Aʻoloau (the plateau), Matautuloa Point, Nuʻuuli, Matafao Peak, Pago Pago, Vaiʻava Strait, Anasosopo, ʻAoa, Cape Matautuloa, and Aunuʻu Island.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p02] After an initial objection, Secretary Leʻiato gave his support and was appointed Chairman of the Territorial Parks and Recreation Committee.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p02] The first field meeting for a parkland acquisition was held between Judge Morrow on behalf of the government and the village council of Vatia to make the Pola Island area a public park.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p02] The dredge *Palolo* was hired from Upolu in January 1966 in order to dredge sand for Utulei Beach.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p02] A specialist in beach developments, Ala Varone of the Army, directed the project.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p02] The centerpiece of the park was to be at the head of Pago Pago Harbor, where it proposed a 13-acre site created by the dredge.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p02] The park would have facilities for sports and recreation as well as facilities for boats and the growing number of Asian immigrants arriving from Korea, Japan, and China.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p02] The Department of Parks and Recreation was created by law in 1980 and the Parks Commission was also established.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p02] In 1981, Governor Peter Tali Coleman appointed Fuga Tolani Teleso as Director of Parks and Recreation.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p02] On May 25, 1984, a groundbreaking ceremony was held at the Onesosopo reclamation to initiate work on the first park in the Eastern District.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p02] At the urging of Paul Cox, High Chief Nafanua of Falealupo, and the Bat Preservers Association, Congressman Fofō Iosefa Fiti Sunia introduced a bill in 1984 which would enter American Samoa into the Federal Fish and Wildlife Restoration Act.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p02] The purpose of the bill was to protect the ancient paleotropical rainforests and the flying fox megabat.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p02] The signing marked the beginning of American Samoa's entry into the U.S.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p02] In July 1987, the National Park Service began establishing a federal park, the National Park of American Samoa.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p02] An initial appropriation of $400,000 was made in 1989.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p02] It contains one of the world's most remarkable rainforest and coastal reef ecologies and spreads across three islands.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p02] One of the most popular sites on Tutuila Island include Pola Rock, a rise of sheer rock formations that protrudes over 400 feet (120 m) above the ocean's surface.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p02] On September 19, 1991, Governor Peter Tali Coleman and Department of the Interior secretary Manuel Lujan signed leases formalizing the establishment of the fiftieth U.S.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p02] American Samoa has seven areas designated as National Natural Landmarks on Tutuila Island.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p02] This program is administrated by the U.S.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p02] National Park Service and the areas contain unique ecological or geological features.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p02] Except Vaiʻava Strait, none of the areas are within the National Park of American Samoa.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p02] Notable terrestrial species include the Pacific tree boa and the Samoa flying fox, which has a three-foot wingspread.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p02] Two snake species can be found in American Samoa: The brahminy blind snake is found on Tutuila, while the Pacific tree boa occurs on Taʻū.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p02] The islands are home to five species of geckos: Pacific slender-toed gecko, oceanic gecko, mourning gecko, stump-toed gecko, and house gecko.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p02] Turtles include the threatened green sea turtle and the endangered hawksbill sea turtle.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p02] Hawksbill sea turtles tend to nest on Tutuila beaches, while the green sea turtle is most common on Rose Atoll.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p02] Tutuila has the highest number of nesting turtles, consisting of around fifty nesting females per year.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p02] American Samoa is home to one species of amphibian: the cane toad.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p02] Biologists estimate that there are over two million toads on Tutuila.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p02] 915 nearshore fish species have been recorded in American Samoa, compared to only 460 nearshore fish species in Hawaii.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p02] With over 950 species of native fish and 250 coral species, American Samoa has the greatest marine biodiversity in the United States.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p02] The National Marine Sanctuary of American Samoa is the largest marine sanctuary in the U.S.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p02] It is home to over 150 species of coral, including some of the largest and oldest corals of their genus in the world.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p02] Megabats are the only native mammal in American Samoa.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p02] The islands are home to two species of fruit bats: Pacific flying fox and Samoa flying fox.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p02] The sheath-tailed bat is another species found here, which is a smaller insect-eating bat.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p02] In 1992, the American Samoa Government banned the hunting of fruit bats to help their populations recover.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p02] The Samoa flying fox is only found in Fiji and the Samoan Islands.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p02] From 1995 to 2000, the population of Samoa flying fox remained stable at about 900 animals on Tutuila, and 100 in the Manuʻa Islands.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p02] As of 2000, scientists from the American Samoa Department of Marine and Wildlife Resource estimated that there are fewer than 5,500 Pacific flying foxes in American Samoa, and an estimated 900 or fewer Samoa flying foxes.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p02] The best and biggest known roost on Tutuila Island for the sheath-tailed bat is in the Anapeʻape Cove near Āfono.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p02] Amalau Valley on Tutuila's north coast offers great roadside views of many bird species and both species of fruit bat.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p02] The valley has been called a prime bird- and bat-watching area.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p02] Sixteen of the Samoan Islands' 34 bird species are found nowhere else on Earth.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p02] This includes the critically endangered tooth-billed pigeon.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p02] Four species of birds are only found in the Manuʻa Islands and not on Tutuila.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p02] These include American Samoa's only parrot, the blue-crowned lory.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p02] Other special birds to Manuʻa are the lesser shrikebill and the friendly ground-dove.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p02] The spotless crake has only been observed on Taʻū Island.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p02] There are more species of birds than all species of reptiles, mammals and amphibians combined.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p02] Native land birds include two honeyeaters: cardinal honeyeater and wattled honeyeater.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p02] Cardinal honeyeaters only occur on Tutuila Island.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p02] The only endemic land bird to American Samoa is the Samoan starling.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p02] Four pigeons are native to American Samoa: Pacific imperial pigeon, many-colored fruit dove, white-capped fruit dove, and shy ground dove.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p02] The local government banned all pigeon hunting in 1992.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p02] The many-colored fruit dove is one of the rarest birds that nest on Tutuila.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p02] Studies in the 1980s estimated their population size at Tutuila to be only around 80 birds.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p02] Amalau Valley has been described as the best place in American Samoa to observe the many-colored fruit dove.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p02] The offshore islet of Pola Island near Vatia is a nesting site for many seabird species and an excellent area to observe seabirds.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p02] The Pola region of Vatia and Rose Atoll are the only places in American Samoa where there are breeding colonies of red-footed boobies.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p02] Birds that depend on freshwater habitat include the Pacific reef heron and Pacific black duck, the Samoan Islands' only species of duck.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/american-samoa-p02] The largest wetland areas are the pala lagoons in Nuʻuuli and Leone as well as Pala Lake on Aunuʻu Island.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/andy-warhol-foundation-for-the-visual-arts-inc-v-goldsmith-p01] Goldsmith had taken her photograph in 1981 on assignment for *Newsweek* and retained copyright on it afterwards; it was not published.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/andy-warhol-foundation-for-the-visual-arts-inc-v-goldsmith-p01] Three years later, *Vanity Fair* licensed the image for Andy Warhol to use as a reference for a silkscreen illustration of Prince to be published, by agreement with Goldsmith, only once, with her credited.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/andy-warhol-foundation-for-the-visual-arts-inc-v-goldsmith-p01] Litigation ensued in federal court between Goldsmith and the Warhol Foundation, which has administered the artist's works since his death, over whether Warhol's reuse of the image had infringed her copyright.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/andy-warhol-foundation-for-the-visual-arts-inc-v-goldsmith-p01] The Southern District of New York sided with the foundation in 2019, but was reversed by the Second Circuit two years later.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/andy-warhol-foundation-for-the-visual-arts-inc-v-goldsmith-p01] The Second Circuit's reversal relied in part on a "clarification" of its 2013 holding in the very similar case of *Cariou v.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/andy-warhol-foundation-for-the-visual-arts-inc-v-goldsmith-p01] Legal commentators, including *Nimmer on Copyright* and another appellate circuit, had criticized *Cariou* in particular and the Second Circuit in general as giving too great a weight to transformative use in determining fair use.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/andy-warhol-foundation-for-the-visual-arts-inc-v-goldsmith-p01] In May 2023, the Court ruled 7–2 that AWF's use of Goldsmith's photographs was not protected by fair use.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/andy-warhol-foundation-for-the-visual-arts-inc-v-goldsmith-p01] Justice Sonia Sotomayor wrote for the majority that the works shared a similar purpose in the depiction of Prince in magazine articles, emphasizing the commercial nature of the product.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/andy-warhol-foundation-for-the-visual-arts-inc-v-goldsmith-p01] Her opinion contained many footnotes disparaging Justice Elena Kagan's combative dissent, which was equally harsh on the majority as she defended the value of transformation in art.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/andy-warhol-foundation-for-the-visual-arts-inc-v-goldsmith-p01] Commentators in the art world feared for the future of appropriation art, popular with artists inspired by Warhol like Richard Prince and Jeff Koons, if artists were to be deterred from creating works by fears of litigation or prohibitive license fees.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/andy-warhol-foundation-for-the-visual-arts-inc-v-goldsmith-p01] Fair use, the unlicensed use of material copyrighted by others in secondary works, was long accepted under English common law, but not well defined.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/andy-warhol-foundation-for-the-visual-arts-inc-v-goldsmith-p01] Within U.S. copyright law, federal judge Joseph Story, later a Supreme Court justice, identified three aspects of fair use to be judged by a court in an 1841 case, *Folsom v.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/andy-warhol-foundation-for-the-visual-arts-inc-v-goldsmith-p01] After over a century of remaining in case law, Congress codified fair use in the Copyright Act of 1976.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/andy-warhol-foundation-for-the-visual-arts-inc-v-goldsmith-p01] Story's three factors became four, with the second split into the nature of the original work, and the amount of it reused.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/andy-warhol-foundation-for-the-visual-arts-inc-v-goldsmith-p01] In 1985 the Supreme Court gave courts guidance on how to apply them in *Harper & Row v.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/andy-warhol-foundation-for-the-visual-arts-inc-v-goldsmith-p01] Nation Enterprises*, a case stemming from the unauthorized publication of the leaked memoirs of former president Gerald R.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/andy-warhol-foundation-for-the-visual-arts-inc-v-goldsmith-p01] The Court held that fair use did not apply to this use of copyrighted material, maintaining that the public's right to know about matters of considerable historical import, such as Ford's decision to pardon his predecessor, was in this case insufficient to supersede the copyright.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/andy-warhol-foundation-for-the-visual-arts-inc-v-goldsmith-p01] Courts remained uncertain enough that five years later, another federal judge, Pierre Leval, then sitting on the Southern District of New York (SDNY), which hears many copyright cases, wrote a *Harvard Law Review* article, "Toward a Fair Use Standard", outlining more specific ideas.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/andy-warhol-foundation-for-the-visual-arts-inc-v-goldsmith-p01] He reviewed cases considering fair use to date, *Harper & Row* included but also cases the Southern District and the Second Circuit Court of Appeals, which has appellate jurisdiction over it, had considered.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/andy-warhol-foundation-for-the-visual-arts-inc-v-goldsmith-p01] He cautioned that such use would not suffice to establish fair use by itself; it could easily be offset by other factors that might weigh in the copyright owner's favor.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/andy-warhol-foundation-for-the-visual-arts-inc-v-goldsmith-p01] Four years later the Supreme Court accepted the concept, citing Leval in *Campbell v.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/andy-warhol-foundation-for-the-visual-arts-inc-v-goldsmith-p01] Acuff-Rose Music, Inc.*, a case that settled a longstanding question over whether parody constituted fair use.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/andy-warhol-foundation-for-the-visual-arts-inc-v-goldsmith-p01] In holding that rap group 2 Live Crew's parody of Roy Orbison's "Oh, Pretty Woman", which the publisher had refused to license to them, was not an infringement, the Court held transformative use to be something judges could consider in assessing the first factor.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/andy-warhol-foundation-for-the-visual-arts-inc-v-goldsmith-p01] "Although such transformative use is not absolutely necessary for a finding of fair use," wrote Justice David Souter for a unanimous Court, "the goal of copyright, to promote science and the arts, is generally furthered by the creation of transformative works.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/andy-warhol-foundation-for-the-visual-arts-inc-v-goldsmith-p01] Warhol settled a 1966 claim brought by the photographer whose image he had used as the basis of his *Flowers Series*.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/andy-warhol-foundation-for-the-visual-arts-inc-v-goldsmith-p01] Fourteen years later Rauschenberg similarly settled with a photographer whose work he had used; until then he had argued fair use with arguments similar to those now accepted as transformative use.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/andy-warhol-foundation-for-the-visual-arts-inc-v-goldsmith-p01] Jeff Koons and Richard Prince became prominent in the art scene during the 1980s, both relying on repurposing the work of others, likewise drawing suit.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/andy-warhol-foundation-for-the-visual-arts-inc-v-goldsmith-p01] A sculpture recreating a postcard that Koons had found and torn the copyright notice off was held not to be fair use by the Second Circuit Court of Appeals in *Rogers v.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/andy-warhol-foundation-for-the-visual-arts-inc-v-goldsmith-p01] Koons*, since it was so similar to the original as to make it "difficult to discern" the parody Koons claimed his work was.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/andy-warhol-foundation-for-the-visual-arts-inc-v-goldsmith-p01] He lost at trial the next year over his unauthorized use of Odie from the *Garfield* comic strip.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/andy-warhol-foundation-for-the-visual-arts-inc-v-goldsmith-p01] Neither case considered transformative use; they were decided after Leval's paper but before *Campbell*.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/andy-warhol-foundation-for-the-visual-arts-inc-v-goldsmith-p01] But 12 years later, with transformative use more clearly established, Koons prevailed when fashion photographer Andrea Blanch alleged his use of part of a photograph she had taken infringed her copyright.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/andy-warhol-foundation-for-the-visual-arts-inc-v-goldsmith-p01] The Supreme Court's test in *Campbell*, it said, "almost perfectly describes" what Koons had done.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/andy-warhol-foundation-for-the-visual-arts-inc-v-goldsmith-p01] Photographer Patrick Cariou sued Richard Prince in 2008 over the latter's *Canal Zone* exhibit, which repurposed 30 images from Cariou's 2000 book *Yes, Rasta* into 28 paintings, some minimally altered from their originals while others were used in collages.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/andy-warhol-foundation-for-the-visual-arts-inc-v-goldsmith-p01] It was feared the verdict would have a chilling effect on appropriation art.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/andy-warhol-foundation-for-the-visual-arts-inc-v-goldsmith-p01] Trial judge Deborah Batts ruled that Prince had not sufficiently transformed most of Cariou's photos, since in his testimony he had eschewed any intended comment on them.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/andy-warhol-foundation-for-the-visual-arts-inc-v-goldsmith-p01] The panel held that Batts had erred by requiring that transformative use be seen as commenting on the original work, or something greater; it was enough that his alterations had changed the mood of the images.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/andy-warhol-foundation-for-the-visual-arts-inc-v-goldsmith-p01] The court held 25 of the 30 images transformative and remanded the other five to the district court to assess them under its standard, vacating the injunction until that decision could be made, a decision hailed by the arts community.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/andy-warhol-foundation-for-the-visual-arts-inc-v-goldsmith-p01] In 2014 Cariou and Prince settled the case before that could happen.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/andy-warhol-foundation-for-the-visual-arts-inc-v-goldsmith-p01] In 1981 photographer Lynn Goldsmith took a series of photographs of Prince at the start of his musical career.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/andy-warhol-foundation-for-the-visual-arts-inc-v-goldsmith-p01] The magazine then commissioned pop-art artist Andy Warhol to create a highly colorized silkscreen using just Prince's head from the photograph, illustrating the feature, "Purple Fame".
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/andy-warhol-foundation-for-the-visual-arts-inc-v-goldsmith-p01] Warhol created 16 variants of the Prince portrait between 1984 and his death in 1987, collectively known as the *Prince Series*, including the notable 1984 *Orange Prince* variant.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/andy-warhol-foundation-for-the-visual-arts-inc-v-goldsmith-p01] All of the 16 works remained in Warhol's private collection while he was alive and after his death were managed by the Andy Warhol Foundation for the Visual Arts (AWF).
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/andy-warhol-foundation-for-the-visual-arts-inc-v-goldsmith-p01] The *Prince Series* works have been exhibited many times in museum shows and galleries around the world including the Museum of Modern Art, Tate and The Andy Warhol Museum.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/andy-warhol-foundation-for-the-visual-arts-inc-v-goldsmith-p01] After Prince's death in 2016, Condé Nast published a commemorative magazine looking back on his life with one of the *Prince Series* variants as the cover image, crediting the Warhol Foundation but not mentioning Goldsmith.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/andy-warhol-foundation-for-the-visual-arts-inc-v-goldsmith-p01] Despite having licensed the photograph and agreed to a co-credit in *Vanity Fair* many years prior, Goldsmith alleged that she had been unaware of the existence of the illustration and the *Prince Series* until she saw the Condé Nast cover.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/andy-warhol-foundation-for-the-visual-arts-inc-v-goldsmith-p01] Goldsmith informed the Foundation that she believed these additional works were copyright violations of her photograph and stated her intent to seek legal action.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/andy-warhol-foundation-for-the-visual-arts-inc-v-goldsmith-p01] The Foundation filed for a preliminary ruling in the Southern District of New York, stating in court papers that it felt like a "shakedown".
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/andy-warhol-foundation-for-the-visual-arts-inc-v-goldsmith-p01] Goldsmith filed a counterclaim seeking to have the Warhol image declared an infringement of her copyright.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/andy-warhol-foundation-for-the-visual-arts-inc-v-goldsmith-p01] He held that Warhol had sufficiently transformed Goldsmith's original photograph under fair use as to show the change of Prince "from a vulnerable, uncomfortable person to an iconic, larger-than-life figure".
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/andy-warhol-foundation-for-the-visual-arts-inc-v-goldsmith-p01] He also noted that Goldsmith had claimed the infringement occurred with the 2016 licensing to Condé Nast, not Warhol's original creation of the work, rendering her claim timely.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/andy-warhol-foundation-for-the-visual-arts-inc-v-goldsmith-p01] Koeltl's analysis relied heavily on *Cariou*.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/andy-warhol-foundation-for-the-visual-arts-inc-v-goldsmith-p01] On the second factor, whether the original photograph had been expressive enough to create a higher bar for the Foundation to establish transformative use, Koeltl found for neither party.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/andy-warhol-foundation-for-the-visual-arts-inc-v-goldsmith-p01] Goldsmith's argument that the photograph had never been published would, he allowed, ordinarily settle the matter in her favor.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/andy-warhol-foundation-for-the-visual-arts-inc-v-goldsmith-p01] But in this instance she had licensed it to be used as Warhol's reference.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/andy-warhol-foundation-for-the-visual-arts-inc-v-goldsmith-p01] His finding of transformative use also further mitigated the importance of this factor.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/andy-warhol-foundation-for-the-visual-arts-inc-v-goldsmith-p01] Goldsmith argued that the third factor, the portion of the original work used, still favored her despite Warhol's use of only Prince's face from her work since that was the "essence" of her image.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/andy-warhol-foundation-for-the-visual-arts-inc-v-goldsmith-p01] "Goldsmith wisely does not contend that Warhol's work has usurped her market for direct sales of [her p]hotograph", Koeltl wrote, beginning to consider the final factor.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/andy-warhol-foundation-for-the-visual-arts-inc-v-goldsmith-p01] "It is plain that the markets for a Warhol and for a Goldsmith fine-art or other type of print are different." Instead she had claimed that the Prince Series posed future harm should she decide to market that photograph or others like it.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/andy-warhol-foundation-for-the-visual-arts-inc-v-goldsmith-p01] Since three of the four factors favored the Foundation, Koeltl granted it summary judgement.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/andy-warhol-foundation-for-the-visual-arts-inc-v-goldsmith-p01] Goldsmith appealed to the Second Circuit.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/andy-warhol-foundation-for-the-visual-arts-inc-v-goldsmith-p01] She said on a GoFundMe page she had set up for the case that she had spent $400,000 by then and sought to raise $2 million.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/andy-warhol-foundation-for-the-visual-arts-inc-v-goldsmith-p01] A panel consisting of circuit judges Gerard E.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/andy-warhol-foundation-for-the-visual-arts-inc-v-goldsmith-p01] Sullivan reversed Koeltl's judgement in March 2021, allowing Goldsmith's lawsuit to proceed.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/andy-warhol-foundation-for-the-visual-arts-inc-v-goldsmith-p01] It considered the same four factors but found that all of them favored Goldsmith's claim.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/andy-warhol-foundation-for-the-visual-arts-inc-v-goldsmith-p01] After reviewing the facts of the case, Lynch's majority opinion turned to the applicable case law, in particular *Cariou*.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/andy-warhol-foundation-for-the-visual-arts-inc-v-goldsmith-p01] "While we remain bound by *Cariou*, and have no occasion or desire to question its correctness on its own facts, our review of the decision below persuades us that some clarification is in order" wrote Lynch.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/andy-warhol-foundation-for-the-visual-arts-inc-v-goldsmith-p01] In considering the stated or assumed intent of the artist as a factor in determining transformative use, Lynch wrote, Koeltl erred: "The district judge should not assume the role of art critic and seek to ascertain the intent behind or meaning of the works at issue.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/andy-warhol-foundation-for-the-visual-arts-inc-v-goldsmith-p01] Lynch acknowledged that Warhol had removed some aspects of Goldsmith's photograph.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/andy-warhol-foundation-for-the-visual-arts-inc-v-goldsmith-p01] On the issue of commercial use, Lynch agreed with Koeltl that the Foundation's purpose in licensing the series and other Warhol works was not purely commercial.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/andy-warhol-foundation-for-the-visual-arts-inc-v-goldsmith-p01] But while that slightly complicated the analysis, he considered it more relevant at other stages of the litigation, such as fashioning equitable remedies.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/andy-warhol-foundation-for-the-visual-arts-inc-v-goldsmith-p01] Lynch also held that Koeltl had erred in his finding on the second factor, the nature of the work.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/andy-warhol-foundation-for-the-visual-arts-inc-v-goldsmith-p01] Just because Goldsmith had licensed it to Condé Nast for an artist to use as a reference did not make it published as she retained the right to decide if and when to publish it, Lynch said.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/andy-warhol-foundation-for-the-visual-arts-inc-v-goldsmith-p01] Lynch had more to say about the third factor, the amount of the original work used.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/andy-warhol-foundation-for-the-visual-arts-inc-v-goldsmith-p01] The Foundation had argued, again, that Warhol removed the distinctive elements of the photograph and thus made the Prince Series distinctly his work.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/andy-warhol-foundation-for-the-visual-arts-inc-v-goldsmith-p01] The Prince Series images "are instantly recognizable as depictions or images of the Goldsmith Photograph itself", said Lynch.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/andy-warhol-foundation-for-the-visual-arts-inc-v-goldsmith-p01] He noted that the Foundation had submitted as evidence other photos of Prince to support its contention, but to him they actually strengthened Goldsmith's case by demonstrating that the series would have looked very different had those other photos been used as the reference.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/andy-warhol-foundation-for-the-visual-arts-inc-v-goldsmith-p01] The Foundation had offered no evidence suggesting that Warhol was specifically interested in Goldsmith's photo as a reference, Lynch added.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/andy-warhol-foundation-for-the-visual-arts-inc-v-goldsmith-p01] In addressing the final factor, the effect on the market for the original work were the use to become widespread, Lynch again began by agreeing with Koeltl, that in this case the primary markets for Goldsmith's photograph and the Prince Series did not overlap.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/andy-warhol-foundation-for-the-visual-arts-inc-v-goldsmith-p01] "Most directly, AWF's licensing of the Prince Series works to Condé Nast without crediting or paying Goldsmith deprived her of royalty payments to which she would have otherwise been entitled", Lynch wrote, moving on to the market for derivative works, in which both parties participated.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/andy-warhol-foundation-for-the-visual-arts-inc-v-goldsmith-p01] The analysis also had to take into account what public benefit might result from the copying.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/andy-warhol-foundation-for-the-visual-arts-inc-v-goldsmith-p01] Finding all four factors favored Goldsmith, and noting that the Foundation had offered no "additional relevant considerations unique to this case that we should take into account", Lynch held for her that the Foundation was not entitled to fair use.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/andy-warhol-foundation-for-the-visual-arts-inc-v-goldsmith-p01] Shortly after the decision was handed down, the Supreme Court decided *Google v.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/andy-warhol-foundation-for-the-visual-arts-inc-v-goldsmith-p01] Oracle*, its first decision on fair use in years.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/andy-warhol-foundation-for-the-visual-arts-inc-v-goldsmith-p01] The Foundation petitioned for rehearing, and the panel granted it to consider its effect on the case, which the Foundation argued called for a different result.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/andy-warhol-foundation-for-the-visual-arts-inc-v-goldsmith-p01] But in an amended version of the ruling issued several months later that took *Google* into account, Lynch was unpersuaded.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/andy-warhol-foundation-for-the-visual-arts-inc-v-goldsmith-p01] The Foundation, he said, "misinterpret[s] both opinions as adopting hard and fast categorical rules of fair use.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/andy-warhol-foundation-for-the-visual-arts-inc-v-goldsmith-p01] Lynch also dismissed the Foundation's claim that the earlier decision effectively outlawed an entire genre of art, likening the case to *Google*'s dispute between two software makers.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/andy-warhol-foundation-for-the-visual-arts-inc-v-goldsmith-p01] Lastly, Lynch considered the Foundation's alternative argument that the district decision be affirmed on the grounds that the two works were not substantially similar.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/andy-warhol-foundation-for-the-visual-arts-inc-v-goldsmith-p01] Normally in copyright lawsuits that question, when raised, was left to a jury, Lynch observed, but did not have to be in this case since opportunity to copy was not a hypothetical but instead a stipulated central fact of the case.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/andy-warhol-foundation-for-the-visual-arts-inc-v-goldsmith-p01] And while it was often remanded to the trial court for consideration, it did not have to be, and in this case since fair use had already been asserted it did not have to be.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/andy-warhol-foundation-for-the-visual-arts-inc-v-goldsmith-p01] Lynch rejected the Foundation's argument for applying the "more discerning observer" test since that was reserved for media, mostly home decor, that typically contained a mix of copyrightable and non-copyrightable elements, which was not the issue with the photographs before the court.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/andy-warhol-foundation-for-the-visual-arts-inc-v-goldsmith-p01] "This is not to say that every use of an exact reproduction constitutes a work that is substantially similar to the original", Lynch concluded.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/andy-warhol-foundation-for-the-visual-arts-inc-v-goldsmith-p01] "But here, given the degree to which Goldsmith's work remains recognizable within Warhol's, there can be no reasonable debate that the works are substantially similar ...
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/andy-warhol-foundation-for-the-visual-arts-inc-v-goldsmith-p01] Prince, like other celebrity artists, was much photographed.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/andy-warhol-foundation-for-the-visual-arts-inc-v-goldsmith-p01] He reassured the owners of other works in the series, and indeed other works by Warhol and other modern artists that might similarly be challenged as derivative works that this decision did not affect them.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/andy-warhol-foundation-for-the-visual-arts-inc-v-goldsmith-p01] AWF claimed that decision subverted the entire purpose of copyright law: to promote creative progress.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/andy-warhol-foundation-for-the-visual-arts-inc-v-goldsmith-p01] Under the Second Circuit's logic, as claimed by the Foundation, an artist like Warhol would be chilled from creating a similar work today in fear of facing claims of infringement, which, under the Circuit's standard, would be upheld.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/andy-warhol-foundation-for-the-visual-arts-inc-v-goldsmith-p01] The Foundation also identified the Supreme Court's decision in *Google LLC v.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/andy-warhol-foundation-for-the-visual-arts-inc-v-goldsmith-p01] Oracle America, Inc.* (2021) related to transformative use as supporting the district court's position.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/andy-warhol-foundation-for-the-visual-arts-inc-v-goldsmith-p01] The Supreme Court granted *certiorari* for the case in March 2022, to be heard during the following term, deciding whether the Foundation's licensing of Orange Prince to Condé Nast infringed Goldsmith's copyright.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/andy-warhol-foundation-for-the-visual-arts-inc-v-goldsmith-p01] Copyright Office sided with Goldsmith in its *amicus curiae* brief, saying Warhol's works were not fair use, as they did not create new expressive meaning, and that a ruling in favor of Warhol would "dramatically expand copyists' ability to appropriate existing works".
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/andy-warhol-foundation-for-the-visual-arts-inc-v-goldsmith-p01] The Court issued its ruling on May 18, 2023, considering only the question of whether the use Condé Nast made of the image licensed from the Foundation could be characterized as transformative in the commercial context, and letting all the Second Circuit's conclusions as to the other factors stand.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/andy-warhol-foundation-for-the-visual-arts-inc-v-goldsmith-p01] Justice Sonia Sotomayor wrote for the majority, joined by all six of the other justices holding for Goldsmith.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/andy-warhol-foundation-for-the-visual-arts-inc-v-goldsmith-p01] Justice Neil Gorsuch wrote a concurring opinion joined by Justice Ketanji Brown Jackson.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/andy-warhol-foundation-for-the-visual-arts-inc-v-goldsmith-p01] Justice Elena Kagan's dissent was joined by Chief Justice John Roberts.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/andy-warhol-foundation-for-the-visual-arts-inc-v-goldsmith-p01] Beyond its holding, the case drew comment for the unusually confrontational tone Sotomayor and Kagan's opinions took with each other.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/andy-warhol-foundation-for-the-visual-arts-inc-v-goldsmith-p01] Sotomayor's ruling, profusely illustrated not just with the images at issue but also other pictures of Prince by Goldsmith and others, as well as some of Warhol's work, largely reiterated the facts of the case and the underlying case law.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/andy-warhol-foundation-for-the-visual-arts-inc-v-goldsmith-p01] At one point she put a smaller version of Warhol's image on Goldsmith's, rotated so it matched the angle on the original image, immediately adjacent, to demonstrate the essential similarity of the two.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/andy-warhol-foundation-for-the-visual-arts-inc-v-goldsmith-p01] Justice Sotomayor concluded that the "purpose and character of the use" weighed against the Foundation.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/andy-warhol-foundation-for-the-visual-arts-inc-v-goldsmith-p01] Analyzing market substitution as inversely related to transformativeness, she found that similarity of use—both the Foundation and Goldsmith competed to license images to magazines—cut against a finding of fair use.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/andy-warhol-foundation-for-the-visual-arts-inc-v-goldsmith-p01] Lynch's warning that judges should not be art critics in this department was partially right, Sotomayor wrote, in that a court should not evaluate the artistic significance of a work.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/andy-warhol-foundation-for-the-visual-arts-inc-v-goldsmith-p01] "[T]he Court's decision seems to me to be exactly right", Gorsuch wrote.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/andy-warhol-foundation-for-the-visual-arts-inc-v-goldsmith-p01] He reiterated Sotomayor's reminder that the only issue before the justices was the Foundation's licensing of the image to illustrate a magazine cover.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/andy-warhol-foundation-for-the-visual-arts-inc-v-goldsmith-p01] "[U]nder the first fair-use factor the salient point is that the purpose and character of the Foundation's use involved competition with Ms.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/andy-warhol-foundation-for-the-visual-arts-inc-v-goldsmith-p01] To know that much is to know the first fair-use factor favors Ms.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/andy-warhol-foundation-for-the-visual-arts-inc-v-goldsmith-p01] Like Sotomayor, Kagan liberally illustrated her opinion with images of artwork.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/andy-warhol-foundation-for-the-visual-arts-inc-v-goldsmith-p01] Not only did she reprint both Goldsmith's photograph and *Orange Prince*, she used other works by Warhol and, in the later sections, paintings by Diego Velázquez, Titian, Giorgione and Francis Bacon to make her points about the historic role of copying and transforming in art.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/andy-warhol-foundation-for-the-visual-arts-inc-v-goldsmith-p01] Kagan accused the majority of deciding the case on the basis of "a marketing decision: In the[ir] view, Warhol's licensing of the silkscreen to a magazine precludes fair use." By doing so they had wrongly mooted the question of what value, if any, Warhol's work had added to Goldsmith's.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/andy-warhol-foundation-for-the-visual-arts-inc-v-goldsmith-p01] "Because the artist had such a commercial purpose, all the creativity in the world could not save him", she wrote.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/andy-warhol-foundation-for-the-visual-arts-inc-v-goldsmith-p01] The majority, Kagan continued, had forgotten that "the more transformative the work, the less commercialism matters", as its decisions in *Campbell v.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/andy-warhol-foundation-for-the-visual-arts-inc-v-goldsmith-p01] Acuff-Rose Music, Inc.* and *Google*, both cases where the allegedly infringing work had been made for primarily and purely commercial purposes respectively, showed.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/andy-warhol-foundation-for-the-visual-arts-inc-v-goldsmith-p01] Indeed, in the latter case the Court had even cited Warhol's work as an example of how transformative use benefited society.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/andy-warhol-foundation-for-the-visual-arts-inc-v-goldsmith-p01] "[W]hat he did to the Goldsmith photo, in service of what objects—counts powerfully in his favor.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/andy-warhol-foundation-for-the-visual-arts-inc-v-goldsmith-p01] Lastly, Kagan said the majority had, by placing such value on the commercial use of *Orange Prince*, conflated the first factor with the fourth, market harm, when it held that the commercial use on the tribute magazine cover adversely affected Goldsmith's market for later use of the image.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/andy-warhol-foundation-for-the-visual-arts-inc-v-goldsmith-p01] "Under the statute, courts are supposed to strike a balance between the two—and thus between rewarding original creators and enabling others to build on their works", she wrote.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/andy-warhol-foundation-for-the-visual-arts-inc-v-goldsmith-p01] The Court, she concluded, had so severely misinterpreted the relevant prior precedents as to chill transformative artistic expression with prior works and "will stifle creativity of every sort".
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/andy-warhol-foundation-for-the-visual-arts-inc-v-goldsmith-p01] In March 2024, after a joint motion by both parties, the Southern District awarded Goldsmith over $21,000 in damages for lost profits and court costs.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/andy-warhol-foundation-for-the-visual-arts-inc-v-goldsmith-p01] Goldsmith said she would not continue action against the remainder of the Prince series, as the statute of limitations had expired.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/andy-warhol-foundation-for-the-visual-arts-inc-v-goldsmith-p02] Goldsmith, who had sold her home in Aspen, Colorado, moved to a Nashville home she mortgaged and set up a GoFundMe page to pay the $2.5 million in legal fees she incurred, said that although she had been "incredibly hopeful", she knew victory was not guaranteed.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/andy-warhol-foundation-for-the-visual-arts-inc-v-goldsmith-p02] "[I]f you don't stand up for your rights, you lose them ...
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/andy-warhol-foundation-for-the-visual-arts-inc-v-goldsmith-p02] I still can't really breathe the sigh of relief that I would like to." Goldsmith was particularly disappointed by Kagan's dissent: "This would be a blow to artists?
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/andy-warhol-foundation-for-the-visual-arts-inc-v-goldsmith-p02] No." Later in 2023 she said her lawyers had agreed that beyond a certain point they would be handling the case *pro bono*.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/andy-warhol-foundation-for-the-visual-arts-inc-v-goldsmith-p02] At that point she had raised merely $68,000 through her GoFundMe page.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/andy-warhol-foundation-for-the-visual-arts-inc-v-goldsmith-p02] Adam Gopnik wrote in *The New Yorker* that he found the combativeness between Sotomayor and Kagan refreshing.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/andy-warhol-foundation-for-the-visual-arts-inc-v-goldsmith-p02] Commentators focused on the art world expressed concern that appropriation art, exemplified by the Prince Series, could suffer as a result of the decision.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/andy-warhol-foundation-for-the-visual-arts-inc-v-goldsmith-p02] "[It] took this already complex area of law and made it even more complicated", wrote NYU law professor Amy Adler in *Art in America*.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/andy-warhol-foundation-for-the-visual-arts-inc-v-goldsmith-p02] "But one thing is clear: it is now far riskier for an artist to borrow from previous work ...
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/andy-warhol-foundation-for-the-visual-arts-inc-v-goldsmith-p02] Any artist who works with existing imagery should now reconsider her practice.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/andy-warhol-foundation-for-the-visual-arts-inc-v-goldsmith-p02] Adler later allowed to Gopnik's brother Blake, a Warhol biographer, writing for *The New York Times*, that Warhol was a "unicorn" in the art world due to the large market for licensing his works.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/andy-warhol-foundation-for-the-visual-arts-inc-v-goldsmith-p02] As a result, the ruling was "irrelevant to most artists".
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/andy-warhol-foundation-for-the-visual-arts-inc-v-goldsmith-p02] She nevertheless saw problems if future creators in Goldsmith's situation sought to charge exorbitant sums for licensing.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/andy-warhol-foundation-for-the-visual-arts-inc-v-goldsmith-p02] Others Gopnik talked to criticized the scope of the decision.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/andy-warhol-foundation-for-the-visual-arts-inc-v-goldsmith-p02] "If it's fair use, it should be fair use to do whatever you want with it", Eric Doeringer, another appropriation artist, told him.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/andy-warhol-foundation-for-the-visual-arts-inc-v-goldsmith-p02] Virginia Rutledge, a former curator who became a lawyer and co-wrote a brief in *Cariou*, feared that artists like Doeringer might "slide down the fear hill" and limit themselves only to creating art from works they could license.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/andy-warhol-foundation-for-the-visual-arts-inc-v-goldsmith-p02] Another Artnet commentator, Ben Davis, said later that this apprehension missed the point.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/andy-warhol-foundation-for-the-visual-arts-inc-v-goldsmith-p02] "I think the interesting question ... is this: Do we actually believe, when it comes to 'fair use,' in a 'celebrity-artist exception?'" The art world's "defensively maximalist" stance on appropriation had led to it giving too much credence to Kagan's dissent, he said.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/andy-warhol-foundation-for-the-visual-arts-inc-v-goldsmith-p02] A decade earlier, Davis recalled, the art world had been less sympathetic when Los Angeles street artist Mr.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/andy-warhol-foundation-for-the-visual-arts-inc-v-goldsmith-p02] Brainwash lost an infringement suit brought by British photographer Dennis Morris over the former's takes on a famous photo of Sid Vicious, takes that involved more alteration than Warhol's work made to Goldsmith.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/andy-warhol-foundation-for-the-visual-arts-inc-v-goldsmith-p02] Sotomayor's emphasis on the use of the image seemed to Davis more useful than Kagan's expansive embrace of transformativeness, especially with the unknown effects artificial intelligence might turn out to have.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/andy-warhol-foundation-for-the-visual-arts-inc-v-goldsmith-p02] "[I]t's not going to help the creative industries in navigating this perilous terrain if they remain completely attached to an automatic romanticization of Warhol-ian appropriation.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states] Works by the federal government of the United States are not protected by copyright and therefore in the public domain.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states] More specifically, the Copyright Act of 1976 which is codified in Title 17 of the United States code states in section 105: "copyright protection under this title is not available for any work of the United States Government".
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states] This act only applies to U.S. domestic copyright as that is the extent of U.S.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states] The U.S. government asserts that it can still hold the copyright to those works in other countries.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states] Publication of an otherwise protected work by the U.S. government does not put that work in the public domain.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states] For example, government publications may include works copyrighted by a contractor or grantee, copyrighted material assigned to the U.S. government, or copyrighted information from other sources.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states] Further, the copyright status of works by subnational governments of the United States is governed by its own set of laws.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states] The first Federal statute concerning copyright in government publications was the Printing Law enacted in 1895.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states] Section 52 of that Act provided that copies of "Government Publications" could not be copyrighted.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states] Prior to 1895, no court decision had occasion to consider any claim of copyright on behalf of the government itself.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states] Courts had, however, considered whether copyright could be asserted as to the text of laws, court decisions, governmental rules, etc., and concluded that such material were not subject to copyright as a matter of public policy.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states] But other material prepared for state governments by their employees – notably the headnotes, syllabi, annotations, etc. prepared by court reporters – had been held copyrightable on behalf of the states.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states] The Copyright Act of 1909 was the first copyright statute to address government publications.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states] Section 7 of the Act (later codified as Section 8 of title 17 U.S.C.) provided that "No copyright shall subsist ... in any publication of the United States Government, or any reprint, in whole or in part, thereof".
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states] Prior to the Printing Act of 1895, no statute governed copyright of U.S. government works.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states] Court decisions had established that an employee of the Federal government had no right to claim copyright in a work prepared by him for the government.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states] Other decisions had held that individuals could not have copyright in books consisting of the text of Federal or state court decisions, statutes, rules of judicial procedures, etc., i.e., governmental edicts and rulings.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states] Copyright was denied on the grounds of public policy: such material as the laws and governmental rules and decisions must be freely available to the public and made known as widely as possible; hence there must be no restriction on the reproduction and dissemination of such documents.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states] While copyright was denied in the text of court decisions, material added by a court reporter on his own – such as leadnotes, syllabi, annotations, indexes, etc. – was deemed copyrightable by him, although he was employed by the government to take down and compile the court decisions.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states] These cases may be said to have established the principle that material prepared by a government employee outside of the scope of the public policy rule was copyrightable; and that the employee who prepared such material on his own could secure copyright therein.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states] There appears to be no court decision before 1895 dealing directly with the question of whether the United States government might obtain or hold copyright in material not within the public policy rule.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states] But the question did arise with respect to state governments.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states] In the nineteenth century much of the public printing for the states was done under contract by private publishers.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states] The publisher would not bear the expense of printing and publishing, however, unless he could be given exclusive rights.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states] To enable the state to give exclusive rights to a publisher, a number of states enacted statutes providing that court reporters or other state officials who prepared copyrightable material in their official capacity should secure copyright in trust for or on behalf of the state.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states] Such copyrights for the benefit of the state were sustained by the courts.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states] Two cases before 1895 may also be noted with regard to the question of the rights of individual authors (or their successors) in material prepared for, or acquired by, the United States government.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states] Appleton*, an artist was held to have no right to secure copyright in drawings prepared by him as a member of Commodore Perry's expedition, since the drawings belonged to the government.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states] Marsh*, where a collection of letters and other private writings of George Washington had been published and copyrighted by his successors, the purchase of the manuscripts by the United States government was held not to affect the copyright.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states] The contention of the defendant that the government's ownership of the manuscripts made them available for publication by anyone was denied.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states] The Printing Law of 1895, which was designed to centralize in the Government Printing Office, the printing, binding, and distribution of federal government documents, contained the first statutory prohibition of copyright in federal government publications.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states] The provision in the Printing Act concerning copyright of government works was probably the result of the "Richardson Affair", which involved an effort in the late 1890s by Representative James D.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states] Richardson (1843–1914) to privately copyright a government-published set of presidential proclamations.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states] The Sections of the Copyright Act that now govern U.S. government work were enacted in 1976 as part of the Copyright Act of 1976.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states] The House Report to the enacted legislation stated that "the basic premise of section 105 of the bill is the same" as section 8 of the former title 17.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states] Section 403 of the 1976 Act introduced a new provision concerning documents consisting preponderantly of one or more government works.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states] In essence, such works would be denied copyright protection unless the required copyright notice included a statement specifically identifying those parts of the work that were *not* U.S. government work, and therefore subject to copyright protection.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states] "To make the notice meaningful rather than misleading", section 403 of the 1976 Act required that, when the copies consist "'preponderantly of one or more works of the United States Government', the copyright notice (if any) identify those parts of the work in which copyright is claimed.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states] A failure to meet this requirement would be treated as an omission of the notice", resulting, absent the application of some exception, in the loss of copyright protection.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states] The Berne Convention Implementation Act of 1988 amended the law to make the use of a copyright notice optional on copies of works published on and after March 1, 1989 and also revised Section 403.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states] After the adoption of this act, a copyright notice was no longer necessary to secure copyright protection.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states] Including the notice, however, does continue to confer certain benefits, notably in the challenging a defendant's claim of innocent infringement, where the question of proper notice may be a factor in assessing damages in infringement actions.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states] Unlike works of the U.S. government, works produced by contractors under government contracts are protected under U.S. copyright law.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states] The holdership of the copyright depends on the terms of the contract and the type of work undertaken.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states] Contract terms and conditions vary between agencies; contracts to NASA and the military may differ significantly from civilian agency contracts.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states] Civilian agencies and NASA are guided by the Federal Acquisition Regulations (FAR).
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states] There are a number of FAR provisions that can affect the ownership of the copyright.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states] *FAR Subpart 27.4—Rights in Data and Copyright* provides copyright guidance for the civilian agencies and NASA.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states] Additionally, some agencies may have their own FAR Supplements that they follow.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states] Under the FAR general data rights clause (FAR 52.227-14), the government has unlimited rights in all data first produced in performance of or delivered under a contract, unless the contractor asserts a claim to copyright or the contract provides otherwise.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states] The express written permission of the Contracting Officer is required before the contractor may assert or enforce the copyright in all other works first produced in the performance of a contract.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states] However, if a contract includes Alternate IV of the clause, the Contracting Officer's approval is not required to assert claim to copyright.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states] Whenever the contractor asserts claim to copyright in works other than computer software, the government, and others acting on its behalf, are granted a license to reproduce, prepare derivative works, distribute, perform and display the copyrighted work.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states] For computer software produced under FAR contract, the scope of the government's license does not include the right to distribute to the public, but for "commercial off the shelf software", the government typically obtains no better license than would any other customer.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states] The federal government can hold copyrights that are transferred to it.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states] Copyright law's definition of work of the United States government does not include work that the government owns but did not create.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states] For example, in 1837, the federal government purchased former U.S.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states] President James Madison's manuscripts from his widow, Dolley Madison, for $30,000.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states] If this is construed as covering copyright as well as the physical papers, it would be an example of such a transfer.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states] "Semper Supra", the official song of the United States Space Force, is an example of a work whose copyright was transferred to the federal government.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states] It was composed in 2022 by James Teachenor and Sean Nelson, who gifted the copyright to the Department of the Air Force.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states] Works by certain independent agencies, corporations and federal subsidiaries may not be considered "government works" and may, therefore, be copyrightable.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states] For instance, material produced by the United States Postal Service are typically subject to normal copyright.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states] Most USPS materials, artwork, and design and all postage stamps as of January 1, 1978, or after are subject to copyright laws.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states] Works of the former United States Post Office Department are in the public domain (due to its former position as a cabinet department).
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states] Secretary of Commerce to secure copyright for works produced by the Department of Commerce under the Standard Reference Data Act.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states] National Defense Authorization Act (NDAA), FY2020, granted civilian members of the faculty at twelve federal government institutions the authority to retain and own copyright of works produced in the course of employment for publication by a scholarly press or journal.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states] The lack of copyright protection for works of the United States government does not apply to works of U.S. subnational governments.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states] Thus, works created by a state or local government may be subject to copyright.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states] Some states have placed much of their work into the public domain by waiving some or all of their rights under copyright law.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states] For example, the constitution and laws of Florida have placed its government's works in the public domain.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states] Unorganized territories (such as American Samoa and the former Trust Territory of the Pacific Islands) are treated, for copyright purposes, as the U.S. government.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states] Their works therefore fall under § 105 and lack copyright protection.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states] Certain works, particularly logos and emblems of government agencies, while not copyrightable, are still protected by other laws that are similar in effect to trademark laws.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states] Such laws are intended to protect indicators of source or quality.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states] For example, some uses of the Central Intelligence Agency logo, name, and initialism are regulated under the CIA Act of 1949 (50 U.S.C. § 403m).
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states] The United States Copyright Office considers "edicts of government", such as judicial opinions, administrative rulings, legislative enactments, public ordinances, and similar official legal documents, not copyrightable for reasons of public policy.
[src:copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states/copyright-status-of-works-by-the-federal-government-of-the-united-states] This applies to such works whether they are federal, state, or local as well as to those of foreign governments.
